description: seaborn is a python visualization library based on matplotlib it provides a high level interface for drawing attractive statistical graphic online documentation is available at seaborn pydata org the doc include a tutorial example gallery api reference and other useful information to build the documentation locally please refer to doc readme md there is also a faq page currently hosted on github seaborn support python and no longer support python installation requires numpy panda and matplotlib some advanced statistical functionality requires scipy and or statsmodels the latest stable release and required dependency can be installed from pypi it is also possible to include optional statistical dependency only relevant for v seaborn can also be installed with conda note that the main anaconda repository lag pypi in adding new release but conda forge c conda forge typically update quickly a paper describing seaborn ha been published in the journal of open source software the paper provides an introduction to the key feature of the library and it can be used a a citation if seaborn prof integral to a scientific publication testing seaborn requires installing additional dependency they can be installed with the dev extra e g pip install dev to test the code run make test in the source directory this will exercise the unit test using pytest and generate a coverage report code style is enforced with flake using the setting in the setup cfg file run make lint to check alternately you can use pre commit to automatically run lint check on any file you are committing just run pre commit install to set it up and then commit a usual going forward seaborn development take place on github http github com mwaskom seabornplease submit bug that you encounter to the issue tracker with a reproducible example demonstrating the problem question about usage are more at home on stackoverflow where there is a seaborn tag

description: theano is a python library that allows you to define optimize and efficiently evaluate mathematical expression involving multi dimensional array it is built on top of numpy theano feature tight integration with numpy a similar interface to numpy s numpy ndarrays are also used internally in theano compiled function transparent use of a gpu perform data intensive computation up to x faster than on a cpu support for float only efficient symbolic differentiation theano can compute derivative for function of one or many input speed and stability optimization avoid nasty bug when computing expression such a log exp x for large value of x dynamic c code generation evaluate expression faster extensive unit testing and self verification includes tool for detecting and diagnosing bug and or potential problem theano ha been powering large scale computationally intensive scientific research since but it is also approachable enough to be used in the classroom ift at the university of montreal theano th of july this is a maintenance release of theano version with no new feature but some deprecation fix we recommend that everybody update to this version highlight since theano is now compatible with python fixed many deprecation warningsa total of people contributed to this release since fish frederic bastienrebecca palmermiro hron okdan foreman mackeyadrian seyboldtabergerontim gatestim odonnellrobert p goldmanduc nguyenigor varfolomeevthomas wiecki

description: datasets is a lightweight library providing two main feature one line dataloaders for many public datasets one liner to download and pre process any of the major public datasets text datasets in language and dialect image datasets audio datasets etc provided on the huggingface datasets hub with a simple command like squad dataset load dataset squad get any of these datasets ready to use in a dataloader for training evaluating a ml model numpy panda pytorch tensorflow jax efficient data pre processing simple fast and reproducible data pre processing for the above public datasets a well a your own local datasets in csv json text png jpeg etc with simple command like processed dataset dataset map process example efficiently prepare the dataset for inspection and ml model evaluation and training documentation colab tutorial find a dataset in the hub add a new dataset to the hub datasets is designed to let the community easily add and share new datasets datasets ha many additional interesting feature thrive on large datasets datasets naturally free the user from ram memory limitation all datasets are memory mapped using an efficient zero serialization cost backend apache arrow smart caching never wait for your data to process several time lightweight and fast with a transparent and pythonic api multi processing caching memory mapping built in interoperability with numpy panda pytorch tensorflow and jax datasets originated from a fork of the awesome tensorflow datasets and the huggingface team want to deeply thank the tensorflow datasets team for building this amazing library more detail on the difference between datasets and tfds can be found in the section main difference between datasets and tfds installation with pip datasets can be installed from pypi and ha to be installed in a virtual environment venv or conda for instance pip install datasets with conda datasets can be installed using conda a follows conda install c huggingface c conda forge datasets follow the installation page of tensorflow and pytorch to see how to install them with conda for more detail on installation check the installation page in the documentation http huggingface co doc datasets installation installation to use with pytorch tensorflow panda if you plan to use datasets with pytorch tensorflow or panda you should also install pytorch tensorflow or panda for more detail on using the library with numpy panda pytorch or tensorflow check the quick start page in the documentation http huggingface co doc datasets quickstart usage datasets is made to be very simple to use the main method are datasets list datasets to list the available datasets datasets load dataset dataset name kwargs to instantiate a dataset this library can be used for text image audio etc datasets here is an example to load a text dataset here is a quick example from datasets import list datasets load dataset print all the available datasets print list datasets load a dataset and print the first example in the training set squad dataset load dataset squad print squad dataset train process the dataset add a column with the length of the context text dataset with length squad dataset map lambda x length len x context process the dataset tokenize the context text using a tokenizer from the transformer library from transformer import great tensorflow datasets here are the main difference between datasets and tfds the script in datasets are not provided within the library but are queried downloaded cached and dynamically loaded upon request datasets also provides evaluation metric in a similar fashion to the datasets i e a dynamically installed script with a unified api this give access to the pair of a benchmark dataset and description: david m cooke francesc alted and others robert a mcleodhttps github com pydata numexprhttp numexpr readthedocs io en latest numexpr is a fast numerical expression evaluator for numpy with it expression that operate on array like a b are accelerated and use le memory than doing the same calculation in python in addition it multi threaded capability can make use of all your core which generally result in substantial performance scaling compared to numpy last but not least numexpr can make use of intel s vml vector math library normally integrated in it math kernel library or mkl this allows further acceleration of transcendent expression the main reason why numexpr achieves better performance than numpy is that it avoids allocating memory for intermediate result this result in better cache utilization and reduces memory access in general due to this numexpr work best with large array numexpr par expression into it own op code that are then used by an integrated computing virtual machine the array operand are split into small chunk that easily fit in the cache of the cpu and passed to the virtual machine the virtual machine then applies the operation on each chunk it s worth noting that all temporary and constant in the expression are also chunked chunk are distributed among the available core of the cpu resulting in highly parallelized code execution the result is that numexpr can get the most of your machine computing capability for array wise computation common speed ups with regard to numpy are usually between x for very simple expression like a and x for relatively complex one like a b a b although much higher speed ups can be achieved for some function and complex math operation up to x in some case numexpr performs best on matrix that are too large to fit in l cpu cache in order to get a better idea on the different speed ups that can be achieved on your platform run the provided benchmark numexpr is available for install via pip for a wide range of platform and python version which may be browsed at http pypi org project numexpr file installation can be performed a if you are using the anaconda or miniconda distribution of python you may prefer to use the conda package manager in this case on most nix system your compiler will already be present however if you are using a virtual environment with a substantially newer version of python than your system python you may be prompted to install a new version of gcc or clang for window you will need to install the microsoft visual c build tool which are free first the version depends on which version of python you have installed http wiki python org moin windowscompilersfor python simply installing the latest version of msvc build tool should be sufficient note that wheel found via pip do not include mkl support wheel available via conda will have mkl if the mkl backend is used for numpy see requirement txt for the required version of numpy numexpr is built in the standard python way you can test numexpr with do not test numexpr in the source directory or you will generate import error numexpr includes support for intel s mkl library this may provide better performance on intel architecture mainly when evaluating transcendental function trigonometrical exponential if you have intel s mkl copy the site cfg example that come with the distribution to site cfg and edit the latter file to provide correct path to the mkl library in your system after doing this you can proceed with the usual building instruction listed above pay attention to the message during the building process in order to know whether mkl ha been detected or not finally you can check the speed ups on your machine by running the bench vml timing py script you can play with different parameter to the set vml accuracy mode and set vml num thread function in the script so a to see how it would affect performance please see the official documentation at numexpr readthedocs io included is a user guide benchmark result and the reference api please see author txt numexpr is distributed under the mit license

description: xarray formerly xray is an open source project and python package that make working with labelled multi dimensional array simple efficient and fun xarray introduces label in the form of dimension coordinate and attribute on top of raw numpy like array which allows for a more intuitive more concise and le error prone developer experience the package includes a large and growing library of domain agnostic function for advanced analytics and visualization with these data structure xarray wa inspired by and borrows heavily from panda the popular data analysis package focused on labelled tabular data it is particularly tailored to working with netcdf file which were the source of xarray s data model and integrates tightly with dask for parallel computing multi dimensional a k a n dimensional nd array sometimes called tensor are an essential part of computational science they are encountered in a wide range of field including physic astronomy geoscience bioinformatics engineering finance and deep learning in python numpy provides the fundamental data structure and api for working with raw nd array however real world datasets are usually more than just raw number they have label which encode information about how the array value map to location in space time etc xarray doesn t just keep track of label on array it us them to provide a powerful and concise interface for example apply operation over dimension by name x sum time select value by label instead of integer location x loc or x sel time mathematical operation e g x y vectorize across multiple dimension array broadcasting based on dimension name not shape flexible split apply combine operation with groupby x groupby time dayofyear mean database like alignment based on coordinate label that smoothly handle missing value x y xr align x y join outer keep track of arbitrary metadata in the form of a python dictionary x attrs documentation http doc xarray devissue tracker http github com description: notefor the latest source discussion etc please visit the github repositoryannoy approximate nearest neighbor oh yeah is a c library with python binding to search for point in space that are close to a given query point it also creates large read only file based data structure that are mmapped into memory so that many process may share the same data to install simply do pip install user annoy to pull down the latest version from pypi for the c version just clone the repo and include annoylib h there are some other library to do nearest neighbor search annoy is almost a fast a the fastest library see below but there is actually another feature that really set annoy apart it ha the ability to use static file a index in particular this mean you can share index across process annoy also decouples creating index from loading them so you can pas around index a file and map them into memory quickly another nice thing of annoy is that it try to minimize memory footprint so the index are quite small why is this useful if you want to find nearest neighbor and you have many cpu s you only need to build the index once you can also pas around and distribute static file to use in production environment in hadoop job etc any process will be able to load mmap the index into memory and will be able to do lookup immediately we use it at spotify for music recommendation after running matrix factorization algorithm every user item can be represented a a vector in f dimensional space this library help u search for similar user item we have many million of track in a high dimensional space so memory usage is a prime concern annoy wa built by erik bernhardsson in a couple of afternoon during hack week euclidean distance manhattan distance cosine distance hamming distance or dot inner product distancecosine distance is equivalent to euclidean distance of normalized vector sqrt co u v work better if you don t have too many dimension like but seems to perform surprisingly well even up to dimensionssmall memory usagelets you share memory between multiple processesindex creation is separate from lookup in particular you can not add more item once the tree ha been created native python support tested with and build index on disk to enable indexing big datasets that won t fit into memory contributed by rene hollander right now it only accepts integer a identifier for item note that it will allocate memory for max id item because it assumes your item are numbered n if you need other id s you will have to keep track of a map yourself annoyindex f metric return a new index that s read write and store vector of f dimension metric can be angular euclidean manhattan hamming or dot a add item i v add item i any nonnegative integer with vector v note that it will allocate memory for max i item a build n tree n job build a forest of n tree tree more tree give higher precision when querying after calling build no more item can be added n job specifies the number of thread used to build the tree n job us all available cpu core a save fn prefault false save the index to disk and load it see next function after saving no more item can be added a load fn prefault false load mmaps an index from disk if prefault is set to true it will pre read the entire file into memory using mmap with map populate default is false a unload unloads a get nns by item i n search k include distance false return the n closest item during the query it will inspect up to search k node which default to n tree n if not provided search k give you a run time tradeoff between better accuracy and speed if you set include distance to true it will return a element tuple with two list in it the second one containing all corresponding distance a get nns by vector v n search k include distance false same but query by vector v a get item vector i return the vector for item i that wa previously added a get distance i j return the distance between item i and j note this used to return the squared distance but ha been changed a of aug a get n item return the number of item in the index a get n tree return the number of tree in the index a on disk build fn prepares annoy to build the index in the specified file instead of ram execute before adding item no need to save after build a set seed seed will initialize the random number generator with the given seed only used for building up the tree i e only necessary to pas this before adding the item will have no effect after calling a build n tree or a load fn note there s no bound checking performed on the value so be careful annoy us euclidean distance of normalized vector for it angular distance which for two vector u v is equal to sqrt co u v the c api is very similar just include annoylib h to get access to it there are just two main parameter needed to tune annoy the number of tree n tree and the number of node to inspect during searching search k n tree is provided during build time and affect the build time and the index size a larger value will give more accurate result but larger index search k is provided in runtime and affect the search performance a larger value will give more accurate result but will take longer time to return if search k is not provided it will default to n n tree where n is the number of approximate nearest neighbor otherwise search k and n tree are roughly independent i e the value of n tree will not affect search time if search k is held constant and vice versa basically it s recommended to set n tree a large a possible given the amount of memory you can afford and it s recommended to set search k a large a possible given the time constraint you have for the query you can also accept slower search time in favour of reduced loading time memory usage and disk io on supported platform the index is prefaulted during load and save causing the file to be pre emptively read from disk into memory if you set prefault to false page of the mmapped index are instead read from disk and cached in memory on demand a necessary for a search to complete this can significantly increase early search time but may be better suited for system with low memory compared to index size when few query are executed against a loaded index and or when large area of the index are unlikely to be relevant to search query using random projection and by building up a tree at every intermediate node in the tree a random hyperplane is chosen which divide the space into two subspace this hyperplane is chosen by sampling two point from the subset and taking the hyperplane equidistant from them we do this k time so that we get a forest of tree k ha to be tuned to your need by looking at what tradeoff you have between precision and performance hamming distance contributed by martin aum ller pack the data into bit integer under the hood and us built in bit count primitive so it could be quite fast all split are axis aligned dot product distance contributed by peter sobot reduces the provided vector from dot or inner product space to a more query friendly cosine space using a method by bachrach et al at microsoft research published in dirk eddelbuettel provides an r version of annoy andy sloane provides a java version of annoy although currently limited to cosine and read only pishen tsai provides a scala wrapper of annoy which us jna to call the c library of annoy atsushi tatsuma provides ruby binding for annoy there is experimental support for go provided by taneli lepp boris nagaev wrote lua binding during part of spotify hack week and a bit afterward jim kang wrote node binding for annoy min seok kim built a scala version of annoy hanabi built a read only rust version of annoy together with dotnet jvm and dart read only binding presentation from new york machine learning meetup about annoyannoy is available a a conda package on linux o x and window ann benchmark is a benchmark for several approximate nearest neighbor library annoy seems to be fairly competitive especially at higher precision it s all written in c with a handful of ugly optimization for performance and memory usage you have been warned the code should support window thanks to qiang kou and timothy riley to run the test execute python setup py nosetests the test suite includes a big real world dataset that is downloaded from the internet so it will take a few minute to execute feel free to post any question or comment to the annoy user group i m fulhack on twitter

description: uniform manifold approximation and projection umap is a dimension reduction technique that can be used for visualisation similarly to t sne but also for general non linear dimension reduction the algorithm is founded on three assumption about the data the data is uniformly distributed on a riemannian manifold the riemannian metric is locally constant or can be approximated a such the manifold is locally connected from these assumption it is possible to model the manifold with a fuzzy topological structure the embedding is found by searching for a low dimensional projection of the data that ha the closest possible equivalent fuzzy topological structure the detail for the underlying mathematics can be found in our paper on arxiv mcinnes l healy j umap uniform manifold approximation and projection for dimension reduction arxiv e print the important thing is that you don t need to worry about that you can use umap right now for dimension reduction and visualisation a easily a a drop in replacement for scikit learn s t sne documentation is available via read the doc new this package now also provides support for densmap the densmap algorithm augments umap to preserve local density information in addition to the topological structure of the data detail of this method are described in the following paper narayan a berger b cho h density preserving data visualization unveils dynamic pattern of single cell transcriptomic variability biorxiv umap depends upon scikit learn and thus scikit learn s dependency such a numpy and scipy umap add a requirement for numba for performance reason the original version used cython but the improved code clarity simplicity and performance of numba made the transition necessary requirement python or greaternumpyscipyscikit learnnumbatqdmrecommended package pynndescentmatplotlibdatashaderholoviewstensorflow installing pynndescent can significantly increase performance and in later version it will become a hard dependency install optionsconda install via the excellent work of the conda forge team the conda forge package are available for linux o x and window bit pypi install presuming you have numba and sklearn and all it requirement numpy and scipy installed if you wish to use the plotting functionality you can useto install all the plotting dependency if you wish to use parametric umap you need to install tensorflow which can be installed either using the instruction at http www tensorflow org install reccomended or usingfor a cpu only version of tensorflow if pip is having difficulty pulling the dependency then we d suggest installing the dependency manually using anaconda followed by pulling umap from pip for a manual install get this package install the requirementsorinstall the packagethe umap package inherits from sklearn class and thus drop in neatly next to other sklearn transformer with an identical calling api there are a number of parameter that can be set for the umap class the major one are a follows n neighbor this determines the number of neighboring point used in local approximation of manifold structure larger value will result in more global structure being preserved at the loss of detailed local structure in general this parameter should often be in the range to with a choice of to being a sensible default min dist this control how tightly the embedding is allowed compress point together larger value ensure embedded point are more evenly distributed while smaller value allow the algorithm to optimise more accurately with regard to local structure sensible value are in the range to with being a reasonable default metric this determines the choice of metric used to measure distance in the input space a wide variety of metric are already coded and a user defined function can be passed a long a it ha been jitd by numba an example of making use of these option umap also support fitting to sparse matrix data for more detail please see the umap documentationumap ha a few signficant win in it current incarnation first of all umap is fast it can handle large datasets and high dimensional data without too much difficulty scaling beyond what most t sne package can manage this includes very high dimensional sparse datasets umap ha successfully been used directly on data with over a million dimension second umap scale well in embedding dimension it isn t just for visualisation you can use umap a a general purpose dimension reduction technique a a preliminary step to other machine learning task with a little care it partner well with the hdbscan clustering library for more detail please see using umap for clustering third umap often performs better at preserving some aspect of global structure of the data than most implementation of t sne this mean that it can often provide a better big picture view of your data a well a preserving local neighbor relation fourth umap support a wide variety of distance function including non metric distance function such a cosine distance and correlation distance you can finally embed word vector properly using cosine distance fifth umap support adding new point to an existing embedding via the standard sklearn transform method this mean that umap can be used a a preprocessing transformer in sklearn pipeline sixth umap support supervised and semi supervised dimension reduction this mean that if you have label information that you wish to use a extra information for dimension reduction even if it is just partial labelling you can do that a simply a providing it a the y parameter in the fit method seventh umap support a variety of additional experimental feature including an inverse transform that can approximate a high dimensional sample that would map to a given position in the embedding space the ability to embed into non euclidean space including hyperbolic embeddings and embeddings with uncertainty very preliminary support for embedding dataframes also exists finally umap ha solid theoretical foundation in manifold learning see our paper on arxiv this both justifies the approach and allows for further extension that will soon be added to the library umap is very efficient at embedding large high dimensional datasets in particular it scale well with both input dimension and embedding dimension for the best possible performance we recommend installing the nearest neighbor computation library pynndescent umap will work without it but if installed it will run faster particularly on multicore machine for a problem such a the dimensional mnist digit dataset with data sample umap can complete the embedding in under a minute a compared with around minute for scikit learn s t sne implementation despite this runtime efficiency umap still produce high quality embeddings the obligatory mnist digit dataset embedded in second with pynndescent installed and after numba jit warmup using a ghz intel core i processor n neighbor min dist the mnist digit dataset is fairly straightforward however a better test is the more recent fashion mnist dataset of image of fashion item again data sample in dimension umap produced this embedding in second n neighbor min dist the uci shuttle dataset sample in dimension embeds well under correlation distance in second note the longer time required for correlation distance computation the following is a densmap visualization of the mnist digit dataset with feature based on the same parameter a above n neighbor min dist densmap reveals that the cluster corresponding to digit is noticeably denser suggesting that there are fewer degree of freedom in the image of compared to other digit umap includes a subpackage umap plot for plotting the result of umap embeddings this package need to be imported separately since it ha extra requirement matplotlib datashader and holoviews it allows for fast and simple plotting and attempt to make sensible decision to avoid overplotting and other pitfall an example of use the plotting package offer basic plot a well a interactive plot with hover tool and various diagnostic plotting option see the documentation for more detail parametric umap provides support for training a neural network to learn a umap based transformation of data this can be used to support faster inference of new unseen data more robust inverse transforms autoencoder version of umap and semi supervised classification particularly for data well separated by umap and very limited amount of labelled data see the documentation of parametric umap or the example notebook for more the densmap algorithm augments umap to additionally preserve local density information in addition to the topological structure captured by umap one can easily run densmap using the umap package by setting the densmap input flag this functionality is built upon the densmap implementation provided by the developer of densmap who also contributed to integrating densmap into the umap package densmap inherits all of the parameter of umap the following is a list of additional parameter that can be set for densmap den frac this determines the fraction of epoch a value between and that will include the density preservation term in the optimization objective this parameter is set to by default note that densmap switch density optimization on after an initial phase of optimizing the embedding using umap den lambda this determines the weight of the density preservation objective higher value prioritize density preservation and lower value closer to zero prioritize the umap objective setting this parameter to zero reduces the algorithm to umap default value is den var shift regularization term added to the variance of local density in the embedding for numerical stability we recommend setting this parameter to which consistently work well in many setting output den when this flag is true the call to fit transform return in addition to the embedding the local radius inverse measure of local density defined in the densmap paper for the original dataset and for the embedding the output is a tuple embedding radius original radius embedding note that the radius are log transformed if false only the embedding is returned this flag can also be used with umap to explore the local density of umap embeddings by default this flag is false for densmap we recommend larger value of n neighbor e g for reliable estimation of local density an example of making use of these option based on a subsample of the mnist dataset see the documentation for more detail documentation is at read the doc the documentation includes a faq that may answer your question if you still have question then please open an issue and i will try to provide any help and guidance that i can if you make use of this software for your work we would appreciate it if you would cite the paper from the journal of open source software if you would like to cite this algorithm in your work the arxiv paper is the current reference additionally if you use the densmap algorithm in your work please cite the following reference if you use the parametric umap algorithm in your work please cite the following reference the umap package is clause bsd licensed we would like to note that the umap package make heavy use of numfocus sponsored project and would not be possible without their support of those project so please consider contributing to numfocus contribution are more than welcome there are lot of opportunity for potential project so please get in touch if you would like to help out everything from code to notebook to example and documentation are all equally valuable so please don t feel you can t contribute to contribute please fork the project make your change and submit a pull request we will do our best to work through any issue with you and get your code merged into the main branch

description: a flexible tool for creating organizing and sharing visualization of live rich data support python visdom aim to facilitate visualization of remote data with an emphasis on supporting scientific experimentation broadcast visualization of plot image and text for yourself and your collaborator organize your visualization space programmatically or through the ui to create dashboard for live data inspect result of experiment or debug experimental code visdom ha a simple set of feature that can be composed for various use case the ui begin a a blank slate you can populate it with plot image and text these appear in window that you can drag drop resize and destroy the window live in envs and the state of envs is stored across session you can download the content of window including your plot in svg tip you can use the zoom of your browser to adjust the scale of the ui the python visdom implementation support callback on a window the demo show an example of this in the form of an editable text pad the functionality of these callback allows the visdom object to receive and react to event that happen in the frontend you can subscribe a window to event by adding a function to the event handler dict for the window id you want to subscribe by calling viz register event handler handler win id with your handler and the window id multiple handler can be registered to the same window you can remove all event handler from a window using viz clear event handler win id when an event occurs to that window your callback will be called on a dict containing additional parameter are defined below right now the following callback event are supported use the top right edit button to inspect all parameter used for plot in the respective window the visdom client support dynamic change of plot parameter a well just change one of the listed parameter the plot will be altered on the fly click the button again to close the property list you can partition your visualization space with envs by default every user will have an env called main new envs can be created in the ui or programmatically the state of envs is chronically saved environment are able to keep entirely different pool of plot you can access a specific env via url http localhost com env main if your server is hosted you can share this url so others can see your visualization too environment are automatically hierarchically organized by the first from the main page it is possible to toggle between different environment using the environment selector selecting a new environment will query the server for the plot that exist in that environment the environment selector allows for searching and filtering for the new enironment from the main page it is possible to compare different environment using the environment selector selecting multiple environment in the check box will query the server for the plot with the same title in all environment and plot them in a single plot an additional compare legend pane is created with a number corresponding to each selected environment individual plot are updated with legend corresponding to x name where x is a number corresponding with the compare legend pane and name is the original name in the legend note the compare envs view is not robust to high throughput data a the server is responsible for generating the compared content do not compare an environment that is receiving a high quantity of update on any plot a every update will request regenerating the comparison if you need to compare two plot that are receiving high quantity of data have them share the same window on a singular env you can use the eraser button to remove all of the current content of an environment this close the plot window for that environment but keep the empty environment for new plot pressing the folder icon open a dialog that allows you to fork or force save the current environment or delete any of your existing environment use of this feature is fully described in the state section env file your envs are loaded upon request by the user by default from home visdom custom path can be passed a a cmd line argument envs are removed by using the delete button or by deleting the corresponding json file from the env dir in case you want the server to pre load all file into cache use the flag eager data loading once you ve created a few visualization state is maintained the server automatically cache your visualization if you reload the page your visualization reappear save you can manually do so with the save button this will serialize the env s state to disk in json including window position you can save an env programmatically this is helpful for more sophisticated visualization in which configuration is meaningful e g a data rich demo a model training dashboard or systematic experimentation this also make them easy to share and reuse fork if you enter a new env name saving will create a new env effectively forking the previous env tip fork an environment before you begin to make edits to ensure that your change are saved seperately you can use the filter to dynamically sift through window present in an env just provide a regular expression with which to match title of window you want to show this can be helpful in use case involving an env with many window e g when systematically checking experimental result note if you have saved your current view the view will be restored after clearing the filter it is possible to manage the view simply by dragging the top of window around however additional feature exist to keep view organized and save common view view management can be useful for saving and switching between multiple common organization of your window using the folder icon a dialog window open where view can be forked in the same way that envs can be saving a view will retain the position and size of all of the window in a given environment view are saved in home visdom view layout json in the visdom filepath note saved view are static and editing a saved view copy that view over to the current view where editing can occur using the repack icon box visdom will attempt to pack your window in a way that they best fit while retaining row column ordering note due to the reliance on row column ordering and reactgridlayout the final layout might be slightly different than what might be expected we re working on improving that experience or providing alternative that give more fine tuned control using the view dropdown it is possible to description: github documentation tutorial issue tracker contactmedpy is a library and script collection for medical image processing in python providing basic functionality for reading writing and manipulating large image of arbitrary dimensionality it main contribution are n dimensional version of popular image filter a collection of image feature extractor ready to be used with scikit learn and an exhaustive n dimensional graph cut package medpy requires python and officially support ubuntu a well a other debian derivative for installation instruction on other operating system see the load the imagethe data is stored in a numpy ndarray the header is an object containing additional metadata such a the voxel spacing now let take a look at some of the image metadata dtype float and description: trimesh is a pure python library for loading and using triangular mesh with an emphasis on watertight surface the goal of the library is to provide a full featured and well tested trimesh object which allows for easy manipulation and analysis in the style of the polygon object in the shapely library the api is mostly stable but this should not be relied on and is not guaranteed install a specific version if you plan on deploying something using trimesh pull request are appreciated and responded to promptly if you d like to contribute here is an up to date list of potential enhancement although thing not on that list are also welcome here s a quick development and contributing guide keeping trimesh easy to install is a core goal thus the only hard dependency is numpy installing other package add functionality but is not required for the easiest install with just numpy pip can generally install trimesh cleanly on window linux and osx the minimal install can load many supported format stl ply gltf glb into numpy array more functionality is available when soft dependency are installed this includes thing like convex hull scipy graph operation networkx faster ray query pyembree vector path handling shapely and rtree xml format like dxml xaml mf lxml preview window pyglet faster cache check xxhash etc to install trimesh with the soft dependency that generally install cleanly on linux osx and window using pip further information is available in the advanced installation documentation here is an example of loading a mesh from file and colorizing it face here is a nicely formatted ipython notebook version of this example also check out the cross section example or possibly the integration of a function over a mesh example trimesh includes an optional pyglet based viewer for debugging and inspecting in the mesh view window opened with mesh show the following command can be used if called from inside a jupyter notebook mesh show display an in line preview using three j to display the mesh or scene for more complete rendering pbr better lighting shaders better off screen support etc pyrender is designed to interoperate with trimesh object you can check out the github network for thing using trimesh a select few quick recommendation glb or ply every time you replace obj with glb an angel get it wing if you want thing like by index face instancing color texture etc glb is a terrific choice gltf glb is an extremely well specified modern format that is easy and fast to parse it ha a json header describing data in a binary blob it ha a simple hierarchical scene graph a great looking modern physically based material system support in dozen to hundred of library and a john carmack endorsment note that gltf is a large specification and trimesh only support a subset of feature loading basic geometry is supported not supported are fancier thing like animation skeleton etc in the wild stl is perhaps the most common format stl file are extremely simple it is basically just a list of triangle they are robust and are a good choice for basic geometry binary ply file are a good step up a they support indexed face and color wavefront obj is also pretty common unfortunately obj doesn t have a widely accepted specification so every importer and exporter implement thing slightly differently making it tough to support it also allows unfortunate thing like arbitrary sized polygon ha a face representation which is easy to mess up reference other file for material and texture arbitrarily interleaf data and is slow to parse give glb or ply a try a an alternative a question that come up pretty frequently is how to cite the library a quick bibtex recommendation if you want to deploy something in a container that us trimesh automated debian slim bullseye based build with trimesh and most dependency are available on docker hub with image tag for latest git short hash for the commit in main i e trimesh trimesh c d and version i e trimesh trimesh docker pull trimesh trimeshhere s an example of how to render mesh using llvmpipe and xvfb inside a container

description: healpy is a python package to handle pixelated data on the sphere it is based on the hierarchical equal area isolatitude pixelization healpix scheme and bundle the healpix c library healpix wa developed to efficiently process cosmic microwave background data from cosmology experiment like boomerang and wmap but it is now used in other branch of astrophysics to store data from all sky survey the target audience used to be primarily the cosmology scientific community but currently anyone interested in handling pixelated data on the sphere is very welcome to propose new feature healpy provides utility to convert between sky coordinate and pixel index in healpix nested and ring schemesfind pixel within a disk a polygon or a strip in the skyapply coordinate transformation between galactic ecliptic and equatorial reference framesapply custom rotation either to vector or full mapsread and write healpix map to disk in fit formatupgrade and downgrade the resolution of existing healpix mapsvisualize map in mollweide gnomonic and cartographic projectionstransform map to spherical harmonic space and back using multi threaded c routinescompute auto and cross power spectrum from map and create map realization from spectrathe documentation can be found at http healpy readthedocs io tutorial at http healpy readthedocs io en latest tutorial html or execute it on mybinderpython or numpy tested with version matplotlibpython development package is required for some distribution e g python dev package for ubuntu astropythe quickest way to install healpy is with pip which automatically fetch the latest version of healpy and any missing dependency if you have installed with pip you can keep your installation up to date by upgrading from time to time see install rst for further detail and other installation option healpy depends on the healpix c and cfitsio c library source code is include with healpy and you do not have to install them separately however if you have them installed already healpy should detect and reuse them instead of building them from source to use your own installation of healpix and cfitsio you will also need pkg confighealpix autotools style c packagecfitsiosee install rst for further instruction building with openmp support the underlying healpix c library can be built to use openmp to speed up some operation on system with multiple core most but not all modern c c compiler support openmp the notable exception being clang if your healpy build fails with an error message about being unable to link against lgomp then this typically mean that healpy detected an already installed healpix c library that wa built with openmp support but you are trying to build healpy with a compiler that doe not support openmp try cleaning the build with python setup py clean all and set the environment variable cc and cxx to point to an openmp capable compiler such a gcc g healpy doe not currently support window see http github com healpy healpy issue incompatibility with cfitisio from heasoft due to a conflict of header file name it is currently not possible to use the cfitsio library provided with the heasoft package for compilation of healpix c heasoft s include directory contains a file called rotmatrix h which clash with healpix s own rotmatrix h compilation problem in the c package some gcc version we have report for and crash with an internal compiler error during compilation of libsharp unfortunately we have not found a workaround for this compiler problem to our knowledge it ha been fixed in gcc and in the x and newer version healpy pixel function e g ang pix do not support bit platform see http github com healpy healpy issue for specific howto question please create a question on stackoverflow and tag it with the healpy tag so that answer will be easily searchable on google if you think you found a bug or you have install issue open an issue on github http github com healpy maintenance and development of healpy via github sponsor

description: http altair viz github ioaltair is a declarative statistical visualization library for python with altair you can spend more time understanding your data and it meaning altair s api is simple friendly and consistent and built on top of the powerful vega lite json specification this elegant simplicity produce beautiful and effective visualization with a minimal amount of code altair is developed by jake vanderplas and brian granger in close collaboration with the uw interactive data lab see altair s documentation site a well a altair s tutorial notebook here is an example using altair to quickly visualize and display a dataset with the native vega lite renderer in the jupyterlab one of the unique feature of altair inherited from vega lite is a declarative grammar of not just visualization but interaction with a few modification to the example above we can create a linked histogram that is filtered based on a selection of the scatter plot if you have a question that is not addressed in the documentation there are several way to ask we ll do our best to get your question answeredaltair provides a python api for building statistical visualization in a declarative manner by statistical visualization we mean the altair api contains no actual visualization rendering code but instead emits json data structure following the vega lite specification the resulting vega lite json data can be rendered in the following user interface to use altair for visualization you need to install two set of toolsthe core altair package and it dependenciesthe renderer for the frontend you wish to use i e jupyter notebook jupyterlab or nteract altair can be installed with either pip or with conda for full installation instruction please see http altair viz github io getting started installation htmlwe maintain a separate github repository of jupyter notebook that contain an interactive tutorial and example http github com altair viz altair notebooksto launch a live notebook server with those notebook using binder or colab click on one of the following badge many excellent plotting library exist in python including the main one each library doe a particular set of thing well however such a proliferation of option creates great difficulty for user a they have to wade through all of these apis to find which of them is the best for the task at hand none of these library are optimized for high level statistical visualization so user have to assemble their own using a mishmash of apis for individual just learning data science this force them to focus on learning apis rather than exploring their data another challenge is current plotting apis require the user to write code even for incidental detail of a visualization this result in an unfortunate and unnecessary cognitive burden a the visualization type histogram scatterplot etc can often be inferred using basic information such a the column of interest and the data type of those column for example if you are interested in the visualization of two numerical column a scatterplot is almost certainly a good starting point if you add a categorical column to that you probably want to encode that column using color or facet if inferring the visualization prof difficult at time a simple user interface can construct a visualization without any coding tableau and the interactive data lab s polestar and voyager are excellent example of such uis we believe that these challenge can be addressed without the creation of yet another visualization library that ha a programmatic api and built in rendering description: the py motmetrics library provides a python implementation of metric for benchmarking multiple object tracker mot while benchmarking single object tracker is rather straightforward measuring the performance of multiple object tracker need careful design a multiple correspondence constellation can arise see image below a variety of method have been proposed in the past and while there is no general agreement on a single method the method of have received considerable attention in recent year py motmetrics implement these metric picture courtesy of bernardin keni and rainer stiefelhagen in particular py motmetrics support clear mot metric and id metric both metric attempt to find a minimum cost assignment between ground truth object and prediction however while clear mot solves the assignment problem on a local per frame basis id measure solves the bipartite graph matching by finding the minimum cost of object and prediction over all frame this blog post by ergys illustrates the difference in more detail py motmetrics implement the following metric the metric have been aligned with what is reported by motchallenge benchmark py motmetrics produce result compatible with popular motchallenge benchmark below are two result taken from motchallenge matlab devkit corresponding to the result of the cem tracker on the training set of the mot dmark in comparison to py motmetrics besides naming convention the only obvious difference areyou can compare tracker result to ground truth in motchallenge format byfor mot you can runto install latest development version of py motmetrics usually a bit more recent than pypi below to install py motmetrics use pippython and numpy panda and scipy is required if no binary package are available for your platform and building source package fails you might want to try a distribution like conda see below to install dependency alternatively for developing clone or fork this repository and install in editing mode in case you are using conda a simple way to run py motmetrics is to create a virtual environment with all the necessary dependenciesthen activate source the motmetrics env and install py motmetrics and run the test in case you already have an environment you install the dependency from within your environment bythe code above update an event accumulator with data from a single frame here we assume that pairwise object hypothesis distance have already been computed note np nan inside the distance matrix it signal that object cannot be paired with hypothesis to inspect the current event history simple print the event associated with the accumulator the above data frame contains raw and mot event to obtain just mot event typemeaning object wa matched to hypothesis with distance similarily object wa matched to hypothesis with distance hypothesis could not be matched to any remaining object and generated a false positive fp possible assignment are computed by minimizing the total assignment distance kuhn munkres algorithm continuing from abovewhile object wa matched object couldn t be matched because no hypothesis are left to pair with object is now tracked by hypothesis leading to a track switch note although a pairing with cost le than is possible the algorithm prefers prefers to continue track assignment from past frame which is a property of mot metric once the accumulator ha been populated you can compute and display metric continuing the example from abovecomputing metric for multiple accumulator or accumulator view is also possiblefinally you may want to reformat column name and how column value are displayed for motchallenge py motmetrics provides predefined metric selector formatters and metric name so that the result look alike what is provided via their matlab devkit in order to generate an overall summary that computes the metric jointly over all accumulator add generate overall true a followsup until this point we assumed the pairwise object hypothesis distance to be known usually this is not the case you are mostly given either rectangle or point centroid of related object to compute a distance matrix from them you can use motmetrics distance module a shown below for large datasets solving the minimum cost assignment becomes the dominant runtime part py motmetrics therefore support these solver out of the boxa comparison for will try to find a lap solver in the order of the list above in order to temporarly replace the default solver usepy motmetrics us the pytest framework to run the test simply cd into the source description: pysparkling provides a faster more responsive way to develop program for pyspark it enables code intended for spark application to execute entirely in python without incurring the overhead of initializing and passing data through the jvm and hadoop the focus is on having a lightweight and fast implementation for small datasets at the expense of some data resilience feature and some parallel processing feature how doe it work to switch execution of a script from pyspark to pysparkling have the code initialize a pysparkling context instead of a sparkcontext and use the pysparkling context to set up your rdds the beauty is you don t have to change a single line of code after the context initialization because pysparkling s api is almost exactly the same a pyspark s since it s so easy to switch between pyspark and pysparkling you can choose the right tool for your use case when would i use it say you are writing a spark application because you need robust computation on huge datasets but you also want the same application to provide fast answer on a small dataset you re finding spark is not responsive enough for your need but you don t want to rewrite an entire separate application for the small answer fast problem you d rather reuse your spark code but somehow get it to run fast pysparkling bypass the stuff that cause spark s long startup time and le responsive feel here are a few area where pysparkling excels small to medium scale exploratory data analysisapplication prototypinglow latency web deploymentsunit testsdocumentation other link description: proper scoring rule for evaluating probabilistic forecast in python evaluation method that are strictly proper cannot be artificially improved through hedging which make them fair method for accessing the accuracy of probabilistic forecast in particular these rule are often used for evaluating weather forecast properscoring run on both python and it requires numpy or later and scipy any recent version should be fine numba is optional but highly encouraged it enables significant speedup e g x faster for crp ensemble and threshold brier score to install use pip pip install properscoring this library focus on the closely related continuous ranked probability score crp and brier score we like these score because they are both interpretable e g crp is a generalization of mean absolute error and easily calculated from a finite number of sample of a probability distribution we will illustrate how to calculate crp against a forecast given by a gaussian random variable to begin import properscoring exact calculation using crp gaussian this is the fastest method numerical integration with crp quadrature from a finite sample with crp ensemble weighted by pdf value with crp ensemble based on the threshold decomposition of crp with threshold brier score in this example we only scored a single observation forecast pair but to reliably evaluate a forecast model you need to average these score across many observation fortunately all scoring rule in properscoring happily accept and return observation a multi dimensional array once you calculate an average score is often useful to normalize them relative to a baseline forecast to calculate a so called skill score defined such that indicates no improvement over the baseline and indicates a perfect forecast for example suppose that our baseline forecast is to always predict a standard normal distribution wa better at predicting these five observation properscoring contains optimized and extensively tested routine for scoring probability forecast these function currently fall into two category continuous ranked probability score crp for an ensemble forecast crp ensemblefor a gaussian distribution crp gaussianfor an arbitrary cumulative distribution function crp quadraturebrier score for binary probability forecast brier scorefor threshold exceedance with an ensemble forecast threshold brier scoreall function are robust to missing value represented by the floating point value nan this library wa written by researcher at the climate corporation the original author include leon barrett description: julius contains different digital signal processing algorithm implemented with pytorch so that they are differentiable and available on cuda note that all the module implemented here can be used with torchscript for now i have implemented along that you might found useful utility in julius requires python to install see the julius documentation for the usage of julius hereafter you will find a few example to get you quickly started this is an implementation of the sinc resample algorithm by julius o smith it is the same algorithm than the one used in resampy but to run efficiently on gpu it is limited to fractional change of the sample rate it will be fast if the old and new sample rate are small after dividing them by their gcd for instance going from a sample rate of to after removing the gcd will be extremely fast while going from to will not julius resampling is faster than resampy even on cpu and when running on gpu it make resampling a completely negligible part of your pipeline except of course for weird case like going from a sample rate of to computing convolution with very large kernel and a stride of can be much faster using fft this implement the same api a torch nn conv d and torch nn functional conv d but with a fft backend dilation and group are not supported fftconv will be faster on cpu even for relatively small tensor a few dozen channel kernel size of on cuda due to the higher parallelism regular convolution can be faster in many case but for kernel size above for a large number of channel or batch size fftconv d will eventually be faster basically when you no longer have idle core that can hide the true complexity of the operation classical finite impulse reponse windowed sinc lowpass filter it will use fft convolution automatically if the filter size is large enough this is the basic block from which you can build high pas and band pas filter see julius filter decomposition of a signal over frequency band in the waveform domain this can be useful for instance to perform parametric eq see usage above you can find speed test and comparison to reference implementation on the benchmark the cpu benchmark are run on a mac book pro with a ghz core intel cpu i the gpus benchmark are run on nvidia v with gb of memory we also compare the validity of our implementation a compared to reference one like resampy or torch nn conv d clone this repository thento run the benchmark julius is released under the mit license this package is named in the honor of julius o smith whose book and website were a gold mine of information for me to learn about dsp go checkout his website if you want to learn more about dsp

description: pyts is a python package for time series classification it aim to make time series classification easily accessible by providing preprocessing and utility tool and implementation of state of the art algorithm most of these algorithm transform time series thus pyts provides several tool to perform these transformation pyts requires to run the example matplotlib is required if you already have a working installation of numpy scipy scikit learn joblib and numba you can easily install pyts using pipor conda via the conda forge channelyou can also get the latest version of pyts by cloning the repositoryafter installation you can launch the test suite from outside the source directory using pytest see the changelog for a history of notable change to pyts the development of this package is in line with the one of the scikit learn community therefore you can refer to their development guide a slight difference is the use of numba instead of cython for optimization the section below give some information about the implemented algorithm in pyts for more information please have a look at the html documentation available via readthedocs if you use pyts in a scientific publication we would appreciate citation to the following paper bibtex entry note the content described in this section corresponds to the main branch not the latest released version you may have to install the latest version to use some of these feature pyts consists of the following module approximation this module provides implementation of algorithm that approximate time series implemented algorithm are piecewise aggregate approximation symbolic aggregate approximation discrete fourier transform multiple coefficient binning and symbolic fourier approximation bag of word this module provide tool to transform time series into bag of word implemented algorithm are wordextractor and bagofwords classification this module provides implementation of algorithm that can classify time series implemented algorithm are kneighborsclassifier saxvsm bossvs learningshapelets timeseriesforest and tsbf datasets this module provides utility to make or load toy datasets a well a fetching datasets from the uea ucr time series classification repository decomposition this module provides implementation of algorithm that decompose a time series into several time series the only description: falconn is a library with algorithm for the nearest neighbor search problem the algorithm in falconn are based on locality sensitive hashing lsh which is a popular class of method for nearest neighbor search in high dimensional space the goal of falconn is to provide very efficient and well tested implementation of lsh based data structure currently falconn support two lsh family for the cosine similarity hyperplane lsh and cross polytope lsh both hash family are implemented with multi probe lsh in order to minimize memory usage moreover falconn is optimized for both dense and sparse data despite being designed for the cosine similarity falconn can often be used for nearest neighbor search under the euclidean distance or a maximum inner product search falconn is written in c and consists of several modular core class with a convenient wrapper around them many mathematical operation in falconn are vectorized through the eigen and ffht library the core class of falconn rely on template in order to avoid runtime overhead we provide a c interface for falconn a well a a python wrapper that us numpy in the future we plan to support more programming language such a julia for c falconn is a header only library and ha no dependency besides eigen which is also header only so falconn is easy to set up for further detail please see our documentation on data set with about million point in around dimension falconn typically requires a few millisecond per query running on a reasonably modern desktop cpu for more detailed result see ann benchmark of erik bernhardsson let u point out that falconn is especially competitive when the ram budget is quite restrictive which is not the regime the above benchmark use maybe your question is already answered in our frequently asked question if you have additional question about using falconn we would be happy to help please send an email to falconn lib gmail com falconn is mainly developed by ilya razenshteyn and ludwig schmidt falconn ha grown out of a research project with our collaborator alexandr andoni piotr indyk and thijs laarhoven many of the idea used in falconn were proposed in research paper over the past year see the documentation if you want to cite falconn in a publication here is the bibliographic information of our research paper bibtex practical and optimal lsh for angular distance alexandr andoni piotr indyk thijs laarhoven ilya razenshteyn ludwig schmidt nip falconn is available under the mit license see license txt note that the third party library in the external folder are distributed under other open source license the eigen library is licensed under the mpl the googletest and googlemock library are licensed under the bsd clause license the pybind library is licensed under a bsd style license

description: kaleido is a cross platform library for generating static image e g png svg pdf etc for web based visualization library with a particular focus on eliminating external dependency the project s initial focus is on the export of plotly j image from python for use by plotly py but it is designed to be relatively straight forward to extend to other web based visualization library and other programming language the primary focus of kaleido at least initially is to serve a a dependency of web based visualization library like plotly py a such the focus is on providing a programmatic friendly rather than user friendly api the kaleido package can be installed from pypi using pip or from conda forge using conda release of the core kaleido c executable are attached a asset to github release at http github com plotly kaleido release version and above of the plotly python library will automatically use kaleido for static image export when kaleido is installed for example then open figure png in the current working directory see the plotly static image export documentation for more information http plotly com python static image export the kaleido python package provides a low level python api that is designed to be used by high level plotting library like plotly here is an example of exporting a plotly figure using the low level kaleido api note this particular example us an online copy of the plotly javascript library from a cdn location so it will not work without an internet connection when the plotly python library us kaleido a in the example above it provides the path to it own local offline copy of plotly j and so no internet connection is required then open figure png in the current working directory a simple a it sound programmatically generating static image e g raster image like pngs or vector image like svgs from web based visualization library e g plotly j vega lite etc is a complex problem it s a problem that library developer have struggled with for year and it ha delayed the adoption of these library among scientific community that rely on print based publication for sharing their research the core difficulty is that web based visualization library don t actually render plot i e color the pixel on their own instead they delegate this work to web technology like svg canvas webgl etc similar to how matplotlib relies on various backends to display figure web based visualization library rely on a web browser rendering engine to display figure when the figure is displayed in a browser window it s relatively straight forward for a visualization library to provide an export image button because it ha full access to the browser for rendering the difficulty arises when trying to export an image programmatically e g from python without displaying it in a browser and without user interaction to accomplish this the python portion of the visualization library need programmatic access to a web browser s rendering engine there are three main approach that are currently in use among python web based visualization library while approach and can both be installed using conda they still rely on all of the system dependency of a complete web browser even the part that aren t actually necessary for rendering a visualization for example on linux both require the installation of system library related to audio libasound so video libffmpeg so gui toolkit libgtk so screensaver libxss so and x libx xcb so support many of these are not typically included in headless linux installation like you find in jupyterhub binder colab azure notebook sagemaker etc also conda is still not a universally available a the pip package manager and neither approach is installable using pip package additionally both and communicate between the python process and the web browser over a local network port while not typically a problem certain firewall and container configuration can interfere with this local network connection the advantage of option is that it introduces no additional system dependency the disadvantage is that it only work when running in a notebook so it can t be used in standalone python script the end result is that all of these library have in depth documentation page on how to get image export working and how to troubleshoot the inevitable failure and edge case while this is a great improvement over the state of affair just a couple of year ago and a lot of excellent work ha gone into making these approach work a seamlessly a possible the fundamental limitation detailed above still result in sub optimal user experience this is especially true when comparing web based plotting library to traditional plotting library like matplotlib and ggplot where there s never a question of whether image export will work in a particular context the goal of the kaleido project is to make static image export of web based visualization library a universally available and reliable a it is in matplotlib and ggplot to accomplish this goal kaleido introduces a new approach the core of kaleido is a standalone c application that embeds the open source chromium browser a a library this architecture allows kaleido to communicate with the chromium browser engine using the c api rather than requiring a local network connection a thin python wrapper run the kaleido c application a a subprocess and communicates with it by writing image export request to standard in and retrieving result by reading from standard out other language wrapper e g r julia scala rust etc can fairly easily be written in the future because the interface relies only on standard in standard out communication using json request by compiling chromium a a library we have a degree of control over what is included in the chromium build in particular on linux we can build chromium in headless mode which eliminates a large number of runtime dependency including the audio video gui toolkit screensaver and x dependency mentioned above the remaining dependency can then be bundled with the library making it possible to run kaleido in minimal linux environment with no additional dependency required in this way kaleido can be distributed a a self contained library that play a similar role to a matplotlib backend compared to orca kaleido brings a wide range of improvement to plotly py user pre compiled wheel for bit linux macos and window are available on pypi and can be installed using pip a with orca kaleido can also be installed using conda kaleido start up about twice a fast a orca and us about half a much system memory kaleido can operate inside docker container based on ubuntu or centos or most any other linux distro released after without the need to install additional dependency using apt or yum and without relying on xvfb a a headless x server kaleido can be used in just about any online notebook service that permit the use of pip to install the kaleido package these include colab sagemaker azure notebook databricks kaggle etc in addition kaleido is compatible with the default docker image used by binder there were occasionally situation where strict security policy and or firewall service would block orca s ability to bind to a local port kaleido doe not have this limitation since it doe not use port for communication while this approach ha many advantage the main disadvantage is that building chromium is not for the faint of heart even on powerful workstation downloading and building the chromium code base take gb of disk space and several hour on linux this work can be done once and distributed a a large docker container but we don t have a similar shortcut for window and macos while motivated by the need of plotly py we made the decision early on to design kaleido to make it fairly straightforward to add support for additional library plugins in kaleido are called scope for more information see http github com plotly kaleido wiki scope plugin architecture while python is the initial target language for kaleido it ha been designed to make it fairly straightforward to add support for additional language for more information description: dhash is a python library that generates a difference hash for a given image a perceptual hash based on neal krawetz s dhash algorithm in this hacker factor blog entry the library is on the python package index pypi and work on both python and python to install it fire up a command prompt activate your virtual environment if you re using one and type the algorithm to create a difference hash is very simple convert the image to grayscaledownsize it to a x thumbnail size mean an by image produce a bit row hash a bit mean the pixel intensity is increasing in the x direction mean it s decreasingdo the same to produce a bit column hash in the y directioncombine the two value to produce the final bit hash valuethe library default to producing a size dhash but you can override this easily by passing size n a a keyword argument to most function for example you can produce a more accurate but slower to work with dhash of bit by specifying size i ve found that dhash is great for detecting near duplicate we found dupe using a size dhash with a maximum delta of bit but because of the simplicity of the algorithm it s not great at finding similar image or duplicate but cropped image you d need a more sophisticated image fingerprint if you want that however the dhash is good for finding exact duplicate and near duplicate for example the same image with slightly altered lighting a few pixel of cropping or very light photoshopping to use the dhash library you need either the wand imagemagick binding or the pillow pil library installed pick one and stick with it they will produce slightly different dhash value due to difference in their grayscale conversion and resizing algorithm if you have both library installed dhash will use wand by default to override this and force use of pillow pil call dhash force pil before using the library to produce a dhash value using wand to produce a dhash value using pillow if you have your own library to convert an image to grayscale and downsize it to x or x for size you can pas dhash row col a list of integer pixel intensity for example from to for example to produce the hash value a a bit integer directly use dhash int image size n to format the hash value in various way use the format function to compute the number of bit different hamming distance between two hash you can use the get num bit different hash hash helper function you can also use dhash to generate the difference hash for a specific image from the command line read the code in dhash py for more detail it s pretty small dhash wa written by ben hoyt and is licensed with a permissive mit license see license txt
