description: fast python collaborative filtering for implicit datasets this project provides fast python implementation of several different popular recommendation algorithm for implicit feedback datasets alternating least square a described in the paper collaborative filtering for implicit feedback datasets and application of the conjugate gradient method for implicit feedback collaborative filtering bayesian personalized ranking logistic matrix factorizationitem item nearest neighbour model using cosine tfidf or bm a a distance metric all model have multi threaded training routine using cython and openmp to fit the model in parallel among all available cpu core in addition the al and bpr model both have custom cuda kernel enabling fitting on compatible gpu s approximate nearest neighbour library such a annoy nmslib and faiss can also be used by implicit to speed up making recommendation implicit can be installed from pypi with installing with pip will use prebuilt binary wheel on x linux window and osx these wheel include gpu support on linux implicit can also be installed with conda the example folder ha a program showing how to use this to compute similar artist on the last fm dataset for more information see the documentation these blog post describe the algorithm that power this library there are also several other blog post about using implicit to build recommendation system this library requires scipy version or later and python version or later gpu support requires at least version of the nvidia cuda toolkit this library ha been tested with python and on ubuntu osx and window simple benchmark comparing the al fitting time versus spark can be found here i d recommend configuring scipy to use intel s mkl matrix library one easy way of doing this is by installing the anaconda python distribution for system using openblas i highly recommend setting export openblas num thread this disables it internal multithreading ability which lead to substantial speedup for this package likewise for intel mkl setting export mkl num thread should also be set released under the mit license

description: the easy way to write your own flavor of pandaspandas added a simple api for registering accessors with panda object panda flavor extends panda extension api by what doe this mean it is now simpler to add custom functionality to panda dataframes and series import this package write a simple python function register the function using one of the following decorator why panda is super handy it general purpose is to be a flexible and powerful data analysis manipulation library panda flavor allows you add functionality that tailor panda to specific field or use case maybe you want to add new write method to the panda dataframe maybe you want custom plot functionality maybe something else accessors in panda are object attached to a attribute on the panda dataframe series that provide extra specific functionality for example panda dataframe plot is an accessor that provides plotting functionality add an accessor by registering the function with the following decorator and passing the decorator an accessor name every dataframe now ha this accessor a an attribute to see this in action check out pdvega phylopandas and pyjanitor using this package you can attach function directly to panda object no intermediate accessor is needed you can install using pip or conda thanks ericmjl pull request are always welcome if you find a bug don t hestitate to open an issue or submit a pr if you re not sure how to do that check out this simple guide if you have a feature request please open an issue or submit a pr panda introduced a simpler api for extending panda this api provided two key decorator register dataframe accessor and register series accessor that enable user to register accessors with panda dataframes and series panda flavor originated a a library to backport these decorator to older version of panda while doing the backporting it became clear that registering method directly to panda object might be a desired feature a well it is likely that panda deliberately chose not implement to this feature if everyone start monkeypatching dataframes with their custom method it could lead to confusion in the panda community the preferred panda approach is to namespace your method by registering an accessor that contains your custom method so how doe method registration work when you register a method panda flavor actually creates and register a this is subtle but important custom accessor class that mimic the behavior of a method by

description: overboard is a lightweight yet powerful dashboard to monitor your experiment a table of hyper parameter with python syntax filtering multiple view of the same data i e custom x y ax hyper parameter visualisation i e bubble plot percentile interval for multiple run i e shaded plot custom visualisation tensor and any custom plot with familiar matplotlib syntax fast client side rendering the training code is kept lightweight you can install the dependency with with conda conda install pyqt pyqtgraph c conda forgewith pip pip install pyqt pyqtgraph if you intend to use custom d plot with pyqtgraph add pyopengl to the list above finally overboard itself can be installed with pip install overboardyour script can log data without installing the full gui and it dependency so your remote gpu cluster doe not need pyqt at all just use pip install overboard loggerand remember to import overboard logger instead of overboard in your script main interface python m overboard log directory logging experiment is simple you can also pas in a meta keyword argument which can be a dict with hyper parameter name and value or other meta data to help organize your experiment these will be displayed in a handy table which support sorting and filtering the meta data can also be an argparse namespace which is useful if your hyper parameter are command line argument parsed with argparse by default a unique folder using the current timestamp is created for the log for full documentation on initialization argument and other method type pydoc overboard on the command line python built in doc viewer you can also check the example directory a note about importing you can either import the logger class from overboard or from overboard logger if you installed the logger only version a described above no dependency then you can only import from overboard logger the easiest way to monitor remote experiment is to mount their directory over sftp and point overboard to it tested with sshfs linux available in most distros fuse mac sftp netdrive window since most of these don t allow overboard to monitor log file with the default light weight method the plot may not update automatically in that case use the command line argument force reopen file depending on the remote server s configuration e g firewall setting you might need to use a vpn to tunnel to the server s network to ensure that the right port are not blocked to you i e having ssh access doe not guarantee sftp access from an external network jo o henriques visual geometry group vgg university of oxford

description: www deeplabcut org deeplabcut is a toolbox for markerless pose estimation of animal performing various task read a short development and application summary below a long a you can see label what you want to track you can use this toolbox a it is animal and object agnostic latest update purple heart deeplabcut support multi animal pose estimation madlc is out of beta rc mode and beta is deprecated thanks to the tester out there for feedback your labeled data will be backwards compatible but not all other step please see the new release for what s new how to install it please see our new paper lauer et al and the new doc on how to use it purple heart we support mulit animal re identification see lauer et al purple heart we have a real time package available http dlclive deeplabcut orgvery quick start pip install deeplabcut gui that includes all gui function or pip install deeplabcut headless version our doc walk you through using deeplabcut and key api point for an overview of the toolbox and workflow for project management see our step by step at nature protocol paper for a deeper understanding and more resource for you to get started with python and deeplabcut please check out our free online course http dlccourse deeplabcut org we provide data and several jupyter notebook one that walk you through a demo dataset to test your installation and another notebook to run deeplabcut from the beginning on your own data we also show you how to use the code in docker and on google colab in we demonstrated the capability for trail tracking reaching in mouse and various drosophila behavior during egg laying see mathis et al for detail there is however nothing specific that make the toolbox only applicable to these task and or specie the toolbox ha already been successfully applied by u and others to rat human various fish specie bacteria leech various robot cheetah mouse whisker and race horse deeplabcut utilized the feature detector resnets readout layer of one of the state of the art algorithm for human pose estimation by insafutdinov et al called deepercut which inspired the name for our toolbox see reference below since this time the package ha changed substantially the code ha been re tooled and re factored since we have added faster and higher performance variant with mobilenetv s efficientnets and our own dlcrnet backbone see pretraining boost out of domain robustness for pose estimation and lauer et al additionally we have improved the inference speed and provided both additional and novel augmentation method added real description: flask compress allows you to easily compress your flask application s response with gzip deflate or brotli it originally started a a fork of flask gzip the preferred solution is to have a server like nginx automatically compress the static file for you if you don t have that option flask compress will solve the problem for you flask compress both add the various header required for a compressed response and compress the response data this make serving compressed static file extremely easy internally every time a request is made the extension will check if it match one of the compressible mime type and whether the client and the server use some common compression algorithm and will automatically attach the appropriate header to determine the compression algorithm the accept encoding request header is inspected respecting the quality factor a described in mdn doc if no requested compression algorithm is supported by the server we don t compress the response if on the other hand multiple suitable algorithm are found and are requested with the same quality factor we choose the first one defined in the compress algorithm option see below if you use pip then installation is simply or if you want the latest github version you can also install flask compress via easy install flask compress is incredibly simple to use in order to start compressing your flask application s asset the first thing to do is let flask compress know about your flask flask application object in many case however one cannot expect a flask instance to be ready at import time and a common pattern is to return a flask instance from within a function only after other configuration detail have been taken care of in these case flask compress provides a simple function flask compress compress init app which take your application a an argument in term of automatically compressing your asset passing your flask flask object to the flask compress compress object is all that need to be done compression is possible per view using the compress compressed decorator make sure to disable global compression first within your flask application s setting you can provide the following setting to control the behavior of flask compress none of the setting are required

description: estimator is an object that estimate the running time of a single argument function you can use it to avoid running a script for too long for example if you want to cluster a large dataset and running it might take too long and cost too much if you use cloud computing you can create a function with one argument x which take a sample with x row and cluster it then you can use estimator to estimate how long it take to run it on the full dataset by providing the actual number of row to the estimate method estimator us a polynomial linear regression model and give more weight to larger number for the training the above code run for about second and then estimate that multiply will take second which is only slightly smaller than the correct number second max time is the maximum time allowed for the estimate function to run if you are using estimator in jupyter you can plot the measurement with the plot method no argument needed which return a matplotlib axessubplot object and display it at the same time

description: pycm is a multi class confusion matrix library written in python that support both input data vector and direct matrix and a proper tool for post classification model evaluation that support most class and overall statistic parameter pycm is the swiss army knife of confusion matrix targeted mainly at data scientist that need a broad array of metric for predictive model and accurate evaluation of a large variety of classifier fig confusionmatrix block diagram pycm is the last version to support python python plotting capability requires matplotlib or seaborn threshold is added in version for real value prediction for more information visit example file is added in version in order to load saved confusion matrix with obj format generated by save obj method for more information visit example sample weight is added in version for more information visit example transpose is added in version in order to transpose input matrix only in direct cm mode relabel method is added in version in order to change confusionmatrix classnames position method is added in version in order to find the index of observation in predict vector which made tp tn fp fn to array method is added in version in order to return the confusion matrix in the form of a numpy array this can be helpful to apply different operation over the confusion matrix for different purpose such a aggregation normalization and combination combine method is added in version in order to merge two confusion matrix this option will be useful in mini batch learning plot method is added in version in order to plot a confusion matrix using matplotlib or seaborn online help function is added in version in order to open each statistic definition in web browserthis option ha been added in version to recommend the most related parameter considering the characteristic of the input dataset the suggested parameter are selected according to some characteristic of the input such a being balance imbalance and binary multi class all suggestion can be categorized into three main group imbalanced dataset binary classification for a balanced dataset and multi class classification for a balanced dataset the recommendation list have been gathered according to the respective paper of each parameter and the capability which had been claimed by the paper is imbalanced parameter ha been added in version so the user can indicate whether the concerned dataset is imbalanced or not a long a the user doe not provide any information in this regard the automatic detection algorithm will be used in version a method for comparing several confusion matrix is introduced this option is a combination of several overall and class based benchmark each of the benchmark evaluates the performance of the classification algorithm from good to poor and give them a numeric score the score of good and poor performance are and respectively after that two score are calculated for each confusion matrix overall and class based the overall score is the average of the score of six overall benchmark which are landis koch fleiss altman cicchetti cramer and matthew in the same manner the class based score is the average of the score of six class based benchmark which are positive likelihood ratio interpretation negative likelihood ratio interpretation discriminant power interpretation auc value interpretation matthew correlation coefficient interpretation and yule s q interpretation it should be noticed that if one of the benchmark return none for one of the class that benchmark will be eliminated in total averaging if the user set weight for the class the averaging over the value of class based benchmark score will transform to a weighted average if the user set the value of by class boolean input true the best confusion matrix is the one with the maximum class based score otherwise if a confusion matrix obtains the maximum of both overall and class based score that will be reported a the best confusion matrix but in any other case the compared object doesn t select the best confusion matrix confusionmatrixcomparefor more information visit herepycm can be used online in interactive jupyter notebook via the binder or colab service try it out now nlnet foundation ha supported the pycm project from version to through the ngi assure fund this fund is set up by nlnet foundation with funding from the european commission s next generation internet program administered by dg communication network content and technology under grant agreement no if you use pycm in your research we would appreciate citation to the following paper download pycm bibgive a if this project helped you if you do like our project and we hope that you do can you please support u our project is not and is never going to be working for profit we need the money just so we can continue doing what we do all notable change to this project will be documented in this file the format is based on keep a changelog and this project adheres to semantic versioning

imbalanced data is known a imbalanced learning or long tail learning under multi class scenario see related paper library resource here currently v imbens includes more than ensemble imbalanced imbalanced ensemble is still under development please see api reference for the latest list here we provide some quick guide to help you get started with imbens we strongly encourage user to check out the example gallery for more comprehensive usage example which demonstrate many advanced feature of imbens taking self paced ensemble a an example it only requires le than line of code to deploy it visualizer documentation and example for more detail fit an imbalancedensemblevisualizerplot performance curvesplot confusion matricesall ensemble classifier in imbens support customizable training logging the training log is controlled by parameter eval datasets eval metric and training verbose of the fit method read more detail in the fit documentation enable auto training logcustomize granularity and content of the training logadd evaluation dataset s customize evaluation metric s class imbalance also known a the long tail problem is the fact that the class are not represented equally in a classification problem which is quite common in practice for instance fraud detection prediction of rare adverse drug reaction and prediction gene family failure to account for the class imbalance often cause inaccurate and decreased predictive performance of many classification algorithm imbalanced learning aim to tackle the class imbalance problem to learn an unbiased model from imbalanced data for more resource on imbalanced learning please refer to awesome imbalanced learning many sampler and utility are adapted from imbalanced learn which is an amazing project check out description: hickle is an hdf based clone of pickle with a twist instead of serializing to a pickle file hickle dump to an hdf file hierarchical data format it is designed to be a drop in replacement for pickle for common data object but is really an amalgam of h py and pickle with extended functionality that is hickle is a neat little way of dumping python variable to hdf file that can be read in most programming language not just python hickle is fast and allows for transparent compression of your data lzf gzip while hickle is designed to be a drop in replacement for pickle or something like json it work very differently instead of serializing json izing it instead store the data using the excellent h py module the main reason to use hickle are the main reason not to use hickle are so if you want your data in hdf or if your pickling is taking too long give hickle a try hickle is particularly good at storing large numpy array thanks to h py running under the hood documentation for hickle can be found at telegraphic github io hickle hickle is nice and easy to use and should look very familiar to those of you who have pickled before in short hickle provides two method a hickle load method for loading hickle file and a hickle dump method for dumping data into hdf here s a complete example a major benefit of hickle over pickle is that it allows fancy hdf feature to be applied by passing on keyword argument on to h py so you can do thing like a detailed explanation of these keywords is given at http doc h py org en latest high dataset html but we give a quick rundown below in hdf datasets are stored a b tree a tree data structure that ha speed benefit over contiguous block of data in the b tree data are split into chunk which is leveraged to allow dataset resizing and compression via filter pipeline filter such a shuffle and scaleoffset move your data around to improve compression ratio and fletcher computes a checksum these file level option are abstracted away from the data model hickle provides several option to store object of custom python class object of class derived from built in class numpy scipy panda and astropy object will be stored using the corresponding loader provided by hickle any other class per default will be stored a binary pickle string starting with version x hickle offer the possibility to define dedicated loader function for custom class and starting with hickle x these can be collected in module package and application specific loader module to create a loader for myclass the create myclass dataset and either the load myclass or the myclasscontainer class have to be defined for dumping content of complex object consisting of multiple sub item which have to be stored a individual h py dataset or h py group object than define create myclass dataset using create group method instead of create dataset and define the corresponding myclasscontainer class in a last step the loader for myclass ha to be registered with hickle this is done by calling hickle lookup loadermanager register class methodfor complex python module package and application defining several class to be dumped and handled by hickle calling hickle lookup loadermanager register class explicitly very quickly becomes tedious and confusing therefore hickle offer from hickle x on the possibility to collect all loader for class and object defined by your module package or application within dedicated loader module and install them along with your module package and application for package and application package the load mypackage py loader module ha to be stored within hickle loader directory of the package directory the first which contains a init py file and should be structured a follows for single file module and application script the load mymodule py or load myapp py file have to be stored within the hickle loader directory located within the same directory a mymodule py or my app py for further example of more complex loader and on how to store bytearrays and string such that they can be compressed when stored see default loader module in hickle loader directory the hdf file format is designed to store several big matrix image and vector efficiently and attach some metadata and to provide a convenient way access the data through a tree structure it is not designed like python pickle format for efficiently mapping the in memory object structure to a file therefore mindlessly storing plenty of tiny object and scalar value without combining them into a single datataset will cause the hdf and thus the file created by hickle explode file size of several gb are likely and possible when a pickle file would just need some mb this can be prevented by create myclass dataset method combining sub item into bigger numpy array or other data structure which can be mapped to h py datasets and load myclass function and or myclasscontainer convert method restoring actual structure of the sub item on load hickle run a lot faster than pickle with it default setting and a little faster than pickle with protocol set so if you do continue to use pickle add the protocol keyword thanks mrocklin for pointing this out for storing python dictionary of list hickle beat the python json encoder but is slower than ujson for a dictionary with entry each containing a length list of random number the time are it should be noted that these comparison are of course not fair storing in hdf will not help you convert something into json nor will it help you serialize a string but for quick storage of the content of a python variable it s a pretty good option install with pip by running pip install hickle from the command line prebuilt python wheel package are available on pypi until h py version and python any newer version have to be built and installed manually install h py with pip by running pip install h py from the commandlineinstall with pip by running pip install hickle form the command lineyou should have python and above installedinstall hdf official page http www hdfgroup org ftp hdf current src unpacked release doc install binary downloads http portal hdfgroup org display support downloads note on window bit install prebuilt binary package for libhdf which is the latest version supporting bit on windowsinstall h py official page http doc h py org en latest build html download hickle via terminal git clone http github com telegraphic hickle git via manual download go to http github com telegraphic hickle and on right hand side you will find download zip filecd to your downloaded hickle directorythen run the following command in the hickle directory python setup py installonce installed from source run python setup py test to check it s all working contribution and bugfixes are very welcome please check out our contribution guideline for more detail on how to contribute to development if you use hickle in academic research we would be grateful if you could reference our paper in the journal of open source software joss

description: hypergraphs are a generalization of graph where each hyper edge also called net can connect more than two vertex the k way hypergraph partitioning problem is the generalization of the well known graph partitioning problem partition the vertex set into k disjoint block of bounded size at most time the average block size while minimizing an objective function defined on the net the two most prominent objective function are the cut net and the connectivity or metric cut net is a straightforward generalization of the edge cut objective in graph partitioning i e minimizing the sum of the weight of those net that connect more than one block the connectivity metric additionally take into account the actual number of block connected by a net by summing the value of all net one accurately model the total communication volume of parallel sparse matrix vector multiplication and once more get a metric that reverts to edge cut for plain graph kahypar is a multilevel hypergraph partitioning framework for optimizing the cut and the metric it support both recursive bisection and direct k way partitioning a a multilevel algorithm it consist of three phase in the coarsening phase the hypergraph is coarsened to obtain a hierarchy of smaller hypergraphs after applying an initial partitioning algorithm to the smallest hypergraph in the second phase coarsening is undone and at each level a local search method is used to improve the partition induced by the coarser level kahypar instantiates the multilevel approach in it most extreme version removing only a single vertex in every level of the hierarchy by using this very fine grained n level approach combined with strong local search heuristic it computes solution of very high quality it algorithm and detailed experimental result are presented in several research publication hypergraph partitioning with variable block weight kahypar ha support for variable block weight if command line option use individual part weight true is used the partitioner try to partition the hypergraph such that each block vx ha a weight of at most bx where bx can be specified for each block individually using the command line parameter part weight b b b bk since the framework doe not yet support perfectly balanced partitioning upper bound need to be slightly larger than the total weight of all vertex of the hypergraph note that this feature is still experimental hypergraph partitioning with fixed vertex hypergraph partitioning with fixed vertex is a variation of standard hypergraph partitioning in this problem there is an additional constraint on the block assignment of some vertex i e some vertex are preassigned to specific block prior to partitioning with the condition that after partitioning the remaining free vertex the fixed vertex are still in the block that they were assigned to the command line parameter fixed f can be used to specify a fix file in hmetis fix file format for a hypergraph with v vertex the fix file consists of v line one for each vertex the ith line either contains to indicate that the vertex is free to move or part id to indicate that this vertex should be preassigned to block part id note that part id start from kahypar currently support three different contraction policy for partitioning with fixed vertex evolutionary framework kahypar e kahypar e enhances kahypar with an evolutionary framework a described in our gecco publication given a fairly large amount of running time this memetic multilevel algorithm performs better than repeated execution of nonevolutionary kahypar configuration hmetis and patoh the command line parameter time limit xxx can be used to set the maximum running time in second parameter partition evolutionary true enables evolutionary partitioning improve existing partition kahypar us direct k way v cycle to try to improve an existing partition specified via parameter part file path to file the maximum number of v cycle can be controlled via parameter vcycles we use the performance profile to compare kahypar to other partitioning algorithm in term of solution quality for a set of algorithm and a benchmark set containing instance the performance ratio relates the cut computed by partitioner p for instance i to the smallest minimum cut of all algorithm i e the performance profile of algorithm p is then given by the function for connectivity optimization the performance ratio are computed using the connectivity value instead of the cut value the value of corresponds to the fraction of instance for which partitioner p computed the best solution while is the probability that a performance ratio is within a factor of of the best possible ratio note that since performance profile only allow to ass the performance of each algorithm relative to the best algorithm the value cannot be used to rank algorithm i e to determine which algorithm is the second best etc in our experimental analysis the performance profile plot are based on the best solution i e minimum connectivity cut each algorithm found for each instance furthermore we choose parameter for all p i and such that a performance ratio if and only if algorithm p computed an infeasible solution for instance i and if and only if the algorithm could not compute a solution for instance i within the given time limit in our performance profile plot performance ratio corresponding to infeasible solution will be shown on the x tick on the x axis while instance that could not be partitioned within the time limit are shown implicitly by a line that exit the plot below since the performance ratio are heavily right skewed the performance profile plot are divided into three segment with different range for parameter to reflect various area of interest the first segment highlight small value while the second segment contains result for all instance that are up to a factor of worse than the best possible ratio the last segment contains all remaining ratio i e instance for which some algorithm performed considerably worse than the best algorithm instance for which algorithm produced infeasible solution and instance which could not be partitioned within the given time limit in the figure we compare kahypar with patoh in quality patoh q and default mode patoh d the k way hmetis k and the recursive bisection variant hmetis r of hmetis p zoltan using algebraic distance based coarsening zoltan algd mondriaan v and the recently published hype algorithm solution quality running time we provide additional resource for all kahypar related publication the karlsruhe hypergraph partitioning framework requires clone the repository including submodules git clone depth recursive git github com simple no deps kahyparthanks to jordan jalving jalving kahypar now also offer a julia interface which can currently be found here kahypar kahypar jl the corresponding dependency can be installed via after that you can use kahypar to partition your hypergraphs like this romain wallon ha created a java interface for kahypar please refer to the readme for a detailed description on how to build and description: python numba package for evaluating and transforming wigner s matrix wigner s j symbol and spin weighted and scalar spherical harmonic these function are evaluated directly in term of quaternion a well a in the more standard form of spherical coordinate and euler angle the convention for this package are described in detail on this page the only true requirement for this code are python and the python package numpy a well a my accompanying quaternion package installation of which is shown below however this package can automatically use numba which us llvm to compile python code to machine code accelerating most numerical function by factor of anywhere from to it is possible to run the code without numba but the most important function are roughly time slower without it the only drawback of numba is that it is nontrivial to install on it own fortunately the best python installer anaconda make it trivial just install the main anaconda package if you prefer the smaller download size of miniconda which come with no extra beyond python you ll also have to run this command assuming you use conda to manage your python installation like any sane python user you can install this package simply asthis should automatically download and install the package quaternion on which this package depends alternatively if you prefer to use pip whether or not you use conda you can also door if you refuse to use conda you might want to install inside your home directory without root privilege anaconda doe this by default anyway this is done by adding user to the above command finally there s also the fully manual option of just downloading both code repository changing to the code directory and issuingthis should work regardless of the installation method a long a you have a compiler hanging around first we show a very simple example of usage with euler angle though it break my heart to do so of course it s always better to use unit quaternion to describe rotation if you need to calculate value of the matrix element for many value of m m it is more efficient to do so all at once the following calculates all mode for from to inclusive finally if you really need to put the pedal to the metal and are willing to guarantee that the input argument are correct you can use a special hidden form of the function here r a and r b are the two complex part of the quaternion defined on this page though the user need not care about that the index variable is assumed to be a two dimensional array of integer where the second dimension ha size three representing the m m index this avoids certain somewhat slower pure python operation involving argument checking reshaping etc the element variable must be a one dimensional array of complex number can be uninitialized which will be replaced with the corresponding value on return again however there is no input dimension checking here so if you give bad input behavior could range from silently wrong to exception to segmentation fault caveat emptor i very much appreciate barry wardell s help in sorting out the relationship between my convention and those of other people and software package especially mathematica s crazy convention this code is of course hosted on github because it is an open source project the hosting is free and all the wonderful feature of github are available including free wiki space and web page hosting pull request a nice interface to the git log etc every change in this code is auomatically tested on travis ci this is a free service for open source project like this one which integrates beautifully with github detecting each commit and automatically re running the test the code is downloaded and installed fresh each time and then tested on python and this ensures that no change i make to the code break either installation or any of the feature that i have written test for finally the code is automatically compiled and the binary hosted for download by conda on anaconda org this is also a free service for open source project like this one the work of creating this code wa supported in part by the sherman fairchild foundation and by nsf grant no phy and ast euler angle are pretty much the worst thing ever and it make me feel bad even supporting them quaternion are faster more accurate basically free of singularity more intuitive and generally easier to understand you can work entirely without euler angle i certainly do you absolutely never need them but if you re so old fashioned that you really can t give them up they are fully supported

description: this project host python implementation of the boruta all relevant feature selection method related blog post http danielhomola com borutapy an all relevant feature selection method download import and do a you would with any other scikit learn method python implementation of the boruta r package this implementation try to mimic the scikit learn interface so use fit transform or fit transform to run the feature selection for more see the doc of these function and the example below original code and method by miron b kursa http m icm edu pl boruta boruta is an all relevant feature selection method while most other are minimal optimal this mean it try to find all feature carrying information usable for prediction rather than finding a possibly compact subset of feature on which some classifier ha a minimal error why bother with all relevant feature selection when you try to understand the phenomenon that made your data you should care about all factor that contribute to it not just the bluntest sign of it in context of your methodology yes minimal optimal set of feature by definition depends on your classifier choice it is the original r package recoded in python with a few added extra feature some improvement include faster run time thanks to scikit learnscikit learn like interfacecompatible with any ensemble method from scikit learnautomatic n estimator selectionranking of featuresfor more detail please check the top of the docstring we highly recommend using pruned tree with a depth between also after playing around a lot with the original code i identified a few area where the core algorithm could be improved altered to make it le strict and more applicable to biological data where the bonferroni correction might be overly harsh percentile a threshold the original method us the maximum of the shadow feature a a threshold in deciding which real feature is doing better than the shadow one this could be overly harsh to control this i added the perc parameter which set the percentile of the shadow feature importance the algorithm us a the threshold the default of which is equivalent to taking the maximum a the r version of boruta doe but it could be relaxed note since this is the percentile it change with the size of the dataset with several thousand of feature it isn t a stringent a with a few dozen at the end of a boruta run two step correction for multiple testing the correction for multiple testing wa relaxed by making it a two step process rather than a harsh one step bonferroni correction we need to correct firstly because in each iteration we test a number of feature against the null hypothesis doe a feature perform better than expected by random for this the bonferroni correction is used in the original code which is known to be too stringent in such scenario at least for biological data and also the original code corrects for n feature even if we are in the th iteration where we only have k n feature left for this reason the first step of correction is the widely used benjamini hochberg fdr following that however we also need to account for the fact that we have been testing the same feature over and over again in each iteration with the same test for this scenario the bonferroni is perfect so it is applied by deviding the p value threshold with the current iteration index if this two step correction is not required the two step parameter ha to be set to false then with perc borutapy behaves exactly a the r version estimator objecta supervised learning estimator with a fit method that return the feature importance attribute important feature must correspond to high absolute value in the feature importance n estimator int or string default if int set the number of estimator in the chosen ensemble method if auto this is determined automatically based on the size of the dataset the other parameter of the used estimator need to be set with initialisation perc int default instead of the max we use the percentile defined by the user to pick our threshold for comparison between shadow and real feature the max tend to be too stringent this provides a finer control over this the lower perc is the more false positive will be picked a relevant but also the le relevant feature will be left out the usual trade off the default is essentially the vanilla boruta corresponding to the max alpha float default level at which the corrected p value will get rejected in both correction step two step boolean default trueif you want to use the original implementation of boruta with bonferroni correction only set this to false max iter int default the number of maximum iteration to perform verbose int default control verbosity of output n feature intthe number of selected feature support array of shape n feature the mask of selected feature only confirmed one are true support weak array of shape n feature the mask of selected tentative feature which haven t gained enough support during the max iter number of iteration ranking array of shape n feature the feature ranking such that ranking i corresponds to the ranking position of the i th feature selected i e estimated best feature are assigned rank and tentative feature are assigned rank

description: routine for plotting area weighted two and three circle venn diagram the simplest way to install the package is via easy install or pip numpy scipy matplotlib the package provides four main function venn venn circle venn and venn circle the function venn and venn circle accept a their only required argument a element list ab ab ab of subset size e g and draw a two circle venn diagram with respective region area in the particular example the region corresponding to subset a and not b will be three time larger in area than the region corresponding to subset a and b alternatively you can simply provide a list of two set or counter i e multi set object instead new in version e g similarly the function venn and venn circle take a element list of subset size abc abc abc abc abc abc abc and draw a three circle area weighted venn diagram alternatively you can provide a list of three set or counter object rather than counting size for all subset the function venn circle and venn circle draw just the circle whereas the function venn and venn draw the diagram a a collection of colored patch annotated with text label in addition version function venn unweighted and venn unweighted draw the venn diagram without area weighting note that for a three circle venn diagram it is not in general possible to achieve exact correspondence between the required set size and region area however in most case the picture will still provide a decent indication the function venn circle and venn circle return the list of matplotlib patch circle object that may be tuned further to your liking the function venn and venn return an object of class venndiagram which give access to constituent patch text element and since version the information about the center and radius of the circle basic example for the three circle case a more elaborate example an example with multiple subplots new in version perhaps the most common use case is generating a venn diagram given three set of object if you ask your question at stackoverflow and tag them matplotlib venn chance are high you ll get an answer from the maintainer of this package report issue and submit fix at github http github com konstantint matplotlib venncheck out the developer readme rst for development related note some alternative mean of plotting a venn diagram a of october are reviewed in the blog post http fouryears eu venn diagram in python the matplotlib subset package visualizes a hierarchy of set a a tree of rectangle the matplotlib venn wordcloud package combine venn diagram with word cloud for a pretty amazing and amusing result

description: alphapredict us a bidirectional recurrent neural network brnn trained on the per residue plddt predicted iddt ca confidence score generated by alphafold af the confidence score from proteome about total protein sequence were used to train the brnn behind alphapredict these confidence score measure the local confidence that alphafold ha in it predicted structure the score go from where represents low confidence and represents high confidence for more information please see highly accurate protein structure prediction with alphafold http doi org s in describing these score the team state that regionds with plddt score of le than should not be interpreted except a possible disordered region the confidence score plddt from the proteome of danio rerio candida albicans mu musculus escherichia coli drosophila melanogaster methanocaldococcus jannaschii plasmodium falciparum mycobacterium tuberculosis caenorhabditis elegans dictyostelium discoideum trypanosoma cruzi saccharomyces cerevisiae schizosaccharomyces pombe rattus norvegicus homo sapiens arabidopsis thaliana zea may leishmania infantum staphylococcus aureus glycine max oryza sativa were used to generate the brnn v and up alphapredict allows for rapid generation of predicted af residue by residue confidence score of any protein of interest this can be used for many application such a generating a quick preview of which region of your protein of interest af might be able to predict with high confidence or which region of your protein might be disordered af is not strictly speaking a disorder predictor and the confidence score are not directly representative of protein disorder therefore any conclusion drawn with regard to disorder from predicted af confidence score should be interpreted with care but they may be able to provide an additional metric to ass the likelihood that any given protein region may be disordered the current brnn v ha on average an error per residue this is the average error rate for the v network we are currently waiting on a new computer to try to generate new network using more data so this will be the most accurate network for the forseeable future if you choose to use other network v ha an average per residue error rate of about v ha an average per residue error rate of about v through v were all network that were tweaked before finishing v so i don t have those number on hand they have error of between and per residue alphapredict is available through pypi to install simply runalternatively you can get alphapredict directly from github to clone the github repository and gain the ability to modify a local copy of the code runthis will install alphapredict locally alphapredict is usable from python first import alphapredict once imported you can begin to generate predicted confidence score the alpha predict function will return a list of predicted confidence score for each residue of the input sequence the input sequence should be a string running would output the alpha graph function will return a graph of predicted confidence score for each residue of the input sequence the input sequence should be a string running would generate we would like to thank the deepmind team for developing alphafold we would like to thank dan griffith from the holehouse lab at washington university school of medicine for developing parrot which is the tool that wa used to generate the brnn behind alphapredict for more info and if you want to generate machine learning network for predicting anything related to protein see http idptools parrot readthedocs io en latest

description: documentation questionnaire dosma basic tutorialdosma is an ai powered python library for medical image analysis this includes but is not limited to we hope that this open source pipeline will be useful for quick anatomy pathology analysis and will serve a a hub for adding support for analyzing different anatomy and scan sequence dosma requires python the core module depends on numpy nibabel nipype panda pydicom scikit image scipy pyyaml and tqdm additional ai feature can be unlocked by installing tensorflow and kera to enable built in registration functionality download elastix detail can be found in the setup documentation to install dosma run if you would like to contribute to dosma we recommend you clone the repository and install dosma with pip in editable mode to run test build documentation and contribute rundosma provides efficient reader for dicom and nifti format built on nibabel and pydicom multi slice dicom data can be loaded in parallel with multiple worker and structured into the appropriate d volume s for example multi echo and dynamic contrast enhanced dce mri scan have multiple volume acquired at different echo time and trigger time respectively these can be loaded into multiple volume with ease dosma s medicalvolume data structure support array like operation arithmetic slicing etc on medical image while preserving spatial attribute and accompanying metadata this structure support numpy interoperability intelligent reformatting fast low level computation and native gpu support for example given medicalvolumes mva and mvb we can do the following dosma is built to be a hub for machine deep learning model a complete list of model and corresponding publication can be found here we can use one of the knee segmentation model to segment a medicalvolume mv and model weight downloaded locally dosma support parallelization for compute heavy operation like curve fitting and image registration image registration is supported thru the elastix transformix library for example we can use multiple worker to register volume to a target and use the registered output for per voxel monoexponential fitting in addition to dosma please also consider citing the work that introduced the method used for analysis

description: actionable recourse is a python library for recourse verification and reporting recourse is the ability of a person to change the prediction of a machine learning model by altering actionable input variable e g income and n credit card a opposed to age or alma mater recourse is an essential aspect of procedural fairness in consumer facing application of machine learning when a consumer is denied a loan by a machine learning model for example they should be able to change the input variable of the model in a way that guarantee approval otherwise this person will be denied the loan so long a the model is deployed and stripped of the ability to influence a decision that affect their livelihood this library provides protect consumer against this harm through verification and reporting these tool can be used to answer question like specific functionality includes the tool are currently designed to support linear classification model and will be extended to cover other kind of model over time you can install the library via pip cplex is fast optimization solver with a python api it is commercial software but free to download for student and faculty at accredited institution to obtain cplex if you have problem installing cplex please check the cplex user manual or the cplex forum we re actively working to improve this package and make it more useful if you come across bug have comment or want to help let u know we welcome any and all contribution for more info on how to contribute check out these guideline thank you community for more about recourse check out our paper actionable recourse in linear classificationif you use this library in your research we would appreciate a citation

description: cattrs is an open source python library for structuring and unstructuring data cattrs work best with attrs class dataclasses and the usual python collection but other kind of class are supported by manually registering converter python ha a rich set of powerful easy to use built in data type like dictionary list and tuples these data type are also the lingua franca of most data serialization library for format like json msgpack yaml or toml data type like this and mapping like dict s in particular represent unstructured data your data is in all likelihood structured not all combination of field name or value are valid input to your program in python structured data is better represented with class and enumeration attrs is an excellent library for declaratively describing the structure of your data and validating it when you re handed unstructured data by your network file system database cattrs help to convert this data into structured data when you have to convert your structured data into data type other library can handle cattrs turn your class and enumeration into dictionary integer and string here s a simple taste the list containing a float an int and a string get converted into a tuple of three ints cattrs work well with attrs class out of the box here s a much more complex example involving attrs class with type metadata consider unstructured data a low level representation that need to be converted to structured data to be handled and use structure when you re done unstructure the data to it unstructured form and pas it along to another library or module use attrs type metadata to add type metadata to attribute so cattrs will know how to structure and destructure them free software mit licensedocumentation http cattrs readthedocs io python version supported and up older python version like and are supported by older version see the changelog convert structured data into unstructured data recursively attrs class and dataclasses are converted into dictionary in a way similar to attrs asdict or into tuples in a way similar to attrs astuple enumeration instance are converted to their value other type are let through without conversion this includes type such a integer dictionary list and instance of non attrs class custom converter for any type can be registered using register unstructure hook convert unstructured data into structured data recursively according to your specification given a a type the following type are supported typing optional t typing list t typing mutablesequence t typing sequence t convert to a list typing tuple both variant tuple t and tuple x y z typing mutableset t typing set t convert to a set typing frozenset t convert to a frozenset typing dict k v typing mutablemapping k v typing mapping k v convert to a dict attrs class with simple attribute and the usual init simple attribute are attribute that can be assigned unstructured data like number string and collection of unstructured data all attrs class and dataclasses with the usual init if their complex attribute have type metadata typing union s of supported attrs class given that all of the class have a unique field typing union s of anything given that you provide a disambiguation function for it custom converter for any type can be registered using register structure hook cattrs come with preconfigured converter for a number of serialization library including json msgpack bson yaml and toml for detail see the cattr preconf package on structured and unstructured data or the case for cattrswhy i use attrs instead of pydanticcattrs i un structuring speedmajor credit to hynek schlawack for creating attrs and it predecessor characteristic cattrs is tested with hypothesis by david r maciver cattrs is benchmarked using perf and pytest benchmark this package wa created with cookiecutter and the audreyr cookiecutter pypackage project template

description: the python package doubleml provides an implementation of the double debiased machine learning framework of chernozhukov et al it is built on top of scikit learn pedregosa et al note that maltekurz and philippbach bug can be reported to the issue tracker at http github com doubleml doubleml for py issue double debiased machine learning chernozhukov et al forthe object oriented implementation of doubleml is very flexible the model class doublemlplr doublemlpliv doublemlirm and doubleiivm implement the estimation of the nuisance function via machine learning method and the computation of the neyman orthogonal score function all other functionality are implemented in the abstract base class doubleml in particular functionality to estimate double machine learning model and to perform statistical inference via the method fit bootstrap confint p adjust and tune this object oriented implementation allows a high flexibility for the model specification in term of it description: efficient set similarity search algorithm in python for even better performance see the go implementation let s say we have a database of user and the book they have read assume that we want to recommend friend for each user and the friend must have read very similar set of book a the user have we can model this a a set similarity search problem by representing each user s book a a set a popular way to measure the similarity between two set is jaccard similarity which give a fractional score between and there are two version of set similarity search problem both can be defined given a collection of set a similarity function and a threshold both version of the problem can be very computationally expensive a the collection can be large and the set size can be large the simple brute force algorithm is o n for and o n for this package includes a python implementation of the all pair binary algorithm in scaling up all pair similarity search paper with additional position filter optimization this algorithm still ha the same worst case complexity a the brute force algorithm however by taking advantage of skewness in empirical distribution of set size and frequency it often run much faster even better than minhash lsh run all pair on ghz intel core i using similarity function jaccard and similarity threshold the running time of datasketch minhashlsh is also shown below for comparison num perm although datasketch minhashlsh is an approximate algorithm and i am using num perm which is quite low it is still a bit slower than the exact algorithm setsimilaritysearch the time for creating datasketch minhash is also included in the end to end time while in practice this time can be saved through pre computation however for ad hoc computation of all pair setsimilaritysearch is still the better choice especially when set are small and fit in memory run query on ghz intel core i using similarity function jaccard and similarity threshold the query set are sampled from the dataset itself the running time of datasketch minhashlsh is also shown below for comparison num perm the indexing time for datasketch minhashlsh including the time for creating datasketch minhash is much worse than setsimilaritysearch nearly x and x therefore setsimilaritysearch is much better for ad hoc computation of the query problem for the scenario in which the same search index is reused for many query problem datasketch minhashlsh is faster than setsimilaritysearch when the set size are large this is easy to understand the size of datasketch minhash is constant wheres a set can be arbitrarily large so the query time for large set is faster when sketch is used however when the set size become smaller the sketch loos it advantage for all pair it take an input of a list of set and output pair that meet the similarity threshold for query it take an input of a list of set and build a search index that can compute any number of query currently the search index only support a static collection of set with no update supported similarity function more to come you can also use the command line program all pair py the input must be one or two file with each line a unique setid token tuple for example when one input file is given it computes all pair when two input file are given it computes query by building a search index on the first collection and querying with set from the second collection effectively computes cross collection pair example usage all pair

description: this is an open source python package for the extraction of radiomics feature from medical imaging with this package we aim to establish a reference standard for radiomic analysis and provide a tested and maintained open source platform for easy and reproducible radiomic feature extraction by doing so we hope to increase awareness of radiomic capability and expand the community the platform support both the feature extraction in d and d and can be used to calculate single value per feature for a region of interest segment based or to generate feature map voxel based not intended for clinical use if you publish any work which us this package please cite the following publication van griethuysen j j m fedorov a parmar c hosny a aucoin n narayan v beet tan r g h fillion robin j c pieper s aerts h j w l computational radiomics system to decode the radiographic phenotype cancer research e e http doi org can join the pyradiomics community on google group here currently support the following feature class aside from the feature class there are also some built in optional filter aside from calculating feature the pyradiomics package includes provenance information in the output this information contains information on used image and mask a well a applied setting and filter thereby enabling fully reproducible feature extraction for more information see the sphinx generated documentation available here alternatively you can generate the documentation by checking out the master branch and running from the root directory the documentation can then be viewed in a browser by opening package root build sphinx html index html furthermore an instruction video is available here pyradiomics is o independent and compatible with python pre built binary are available on pypi and conda to install pyradiomics ensure you have python installed and run detailed installation instruction a well a instruction for building pyradiomics from source are available in the documentation pyradiomics also support docker currently docker are available the first one is a jupyter notebook with pyradiomics pre installed with example notebook to get the docker the radiomics notebook docker ha an exposed volume data that can be mapped to the host system directory for example to mount the current directory or for a le secure notebook skip the randomly generated tokenand open the local webpage at http localhost with the current directory at http localhost tree data the second is a docker which expose the pyradiomics cli interface to get the cli docker you can then use the pyradiomics cli a follows for more information on using docker see herepyradiomics can be easily used in a python script through the featureextractor module furthermore pyradiomics provides a commandline script pyradiomics for both single image extraction and batchprocessing finally a convenient front end interface is provided a the radiomics extension for d slicer available here see also the requirement file pyradiomics is also available a an extension to d slicer download and install the d slicer nightly build the extension is then available in the extension manager under slicerradiomics this package is covered by the open source clause bsd license department of radiation oncology dana farber cancer institute brigham and woman s hospital harvard medical school boston ma department of radiology brigham and woman s hospital harvard medical school boston ma department of radiology netherlands cancer institute amsterdam the netherlands grow school for oncology and developmental biology maastricht university medical center maastricht the netherlands kitware isomicswe are happy to help you with any question please contact u on the radiomics community section of the d slicer discourse we welcome contribution to pyradiomics please read the contributing guideline on how to contribute to pyradiomics this work wa supported in part by the u national cancer institute grant u ca quantitative radiomics system decoding the tumor phenotype

visualization module is also provided for rendering the object s the interleaved data can also be used by more modern renderers thought vbos or vaos currently the most commonly used feature in the specification ha been implemented we currently don t support parameter space vertex line element or smoothing group create an issue or pull request on github if needed feature are missing the package is on pypi or can be cloned on github also check out the roadmap for future plan basic example loading an obj file a more complex examplewhen cache true the interleaved vertex data is written a float to a bin file after the file is loaded a json file is also generated describing the content of the binary file the binary file will be loaded the next time we attempt to load the obj file reducing the loading time significantly test have shown loading time reduction by to time depending on the size and structure of the original obj file loading myfile obj will generate the following file in the description: this is merely a python port of kurt spencer s original code released to the public domain and neatly wrapped up in a package the master branch contains the latest potentially unstable code for the latest stable version please refer to the version tag for now this version ha been tested with python on linux macos and window update for v installation basic usage for more advanced example see the file in the test and example directory available function opensimplex seed seed random seed opensimplex noise x y opensimplex noise array x y opensimplex noise x y z opensimplex noise array x y z opensimplex noise x y z w opensimplex noise array x y z w running test and benchmark setup a development environment and then run the test or the benchmark is this relevantly different enough to avoid any real trouble with the original patent if you read the patent claim claim talk about the hardware implementation optimized gradient generator most software implementation of simplex noise don t use this anyway and opensimplex noise certainly doesn t claim talk about using x y z x s y s z s where s x y z to transform the input render space coordinate onto a simplical grid with the intention to make all of the scissor simplices approximately regular opensimplex noise in d us s x y z to transform the input point to a point on the simplectic honeycomb lattice so that the simplices bounding the hyper cube at and work out to be regular it then mathematically work out that s x y z is needed for the inverse transform but that s performing a different and opposite function claim are specific to the scissor simplex lattice simplex noise divide the squashed n dimensional hyper cube into n simplices based on ordered edge traversal whereas opensimplex noise divide the stretched n dimensional hyper cube into n polytopes simplices rectified simplices birectified simplices etc based on the separation hyper plane at integer value of x y z another interesting point is that if you read all of the claim none of them appear to apply to the d analogue of simplex noise so long a it us a gradient generator separate from the one described in claim the skew function in claim only applies to d and explicitly refers to n and none of the patent claim speak about using surflets spherically symmetric kernel to generate the image with texture that do not have visible grid artifact which is probably the biggest similarity between the two algorithm kurt spencer original workalex python port and package authorowen raccuglia test case go module u redblobgames fixed conversion for java s long type see redditand all the other github contributor and bug hunter thanks while the original work wa released to the public domain by kurt this package is using the mit license please see the file license for detail example image visualising d d and d noise on a d plane using the default seed d noise d noise d noise

description: this python package implement blend mode for image the blend mode package enables blending different image or image layer by mean of blend mode these mode are commonly found in graphic program like adobe photoshop or gimp blending through blend mode allows to mix image in a variety of way this package currently support the following blend mode name of the respective function in the package in italic soft light blend mode soft light lighten only blend mode lighten only dodge blend mode dodge addition blend mode addition darken only blend mode darken only multiply blend mode multiply hard light blend mode hard light difference blend mode difference subtract blend mode subtract grain extract known from gimp blend mode grain extract grain merge known from gimp blend mode grain merge divide blend mode divide overlay blend mode overlay normal blend mode normal the intensity of blending can be controlled by mean of an opacity parameter that is passed into the function see usage for more information the blend mode package is optimized for speed it take advantage of vectorization through numpy further speedup can be achieved when implementing the package in cython however cython implementation is not part of this package the blend mode function take image data expressed a array a an input these image data are usually obtained through function from image processing package two popular image processing package in python are pil or it fork pillow and opencv the example in this chapter show how to blend image using these package a typical blend mode operation is called like this the blend mode function expect numpy float array in the format pixel in dimension pixel in dimension a an input both image need to have the same size so the pixel in dimension must be the same for bg img and fg img same applies to the pixel in dimension thus a valid shape of the array would be bg img shape and fg img shape the order of the channel in the third dimension should be r g b a where a is the alpha channel all value should be float in the range value the blend mode function return array in the same format a the input format the following example show how to use the blend mode package in typical application the example are structured in three part load background and foreground image the foreground image is to be blended onto the background image use the blend mode package to blend the two image via the soft light blend mode the package support multiple blend mode see the description for a full list display the blended image the following example show how to use the blend mode package with the pil or pillow package the following example show how to use the blend mode package with opencv the blend mode package can be installed through pip pip install blend modesthe blend mode package need numpy to function correctly for loading image the following package have been successfully used pilpillowopencvblend mode are further description: pyemd is a python wrapper for ofir pele and michael werman s implementation of the earth mover s distance that allows it to be used with numpy if you use this code please cite the paper listed at the end of this document you can also get the associated minimum cost flow you can also calculate the emd directly from two array of observation argument first histogram np ndarray a d array of type np float of length n second histogram np ndarray a d array of np float of length n distance matrix np ndarray a d array of np float of size at least n n this defines the underlying metric or ground distance by giving the pairwise distance between the histogram bin it must represent a metric there is no warning if it doesn t keyword argument extra mass penalty float the penalty for extra mass if you want the resulting distance to be a metric it should be at least half the diameter of the space maximum possible distance between any two point if you want partial matching you can set it to zero but then the resulting distance is not guaranteed to be a metric the default value is which mean the maximum value in the distance matrix is used return float the emd value argument are the same a for emd return tuple float list list float the emd value and the associated minimum cost flow argument first array iterable a d array of sample used to generate a histogram second array iterable a d array of sample used to generate a histogram keyword argument extra mass penalty float same a for emd distance string or function a string or function implementing a metric on a d np ndarray default to the euclidean distance currently limited to euclidean or your own function which must take a d array and return a square d array of pairwise distance normalized boolean if true default treat histogram a fraction of the dataset if false treat histogram a count in the latter case the emd will vary greatly by array length bin int or string the number of bin to include in the generated histogram if a string must be one of the bin selection algorithm accepted by np histogram default to auto which give the maximum of the sturges and fd estimator range tuple int int the lower and upper range of the bin passed to numpy histogram default to the range of the union of first array and second array note if the given range is not a superset of the default range no warning will be given return float the emd value between the histogram of first array and second array emd and emd with flow the distance matrix is assumed to represent a metric there is no check to ensure that this is true see the documentation in pyemd lib emd hat hpp for more information the histogram and distance matrix must be numpy array of type np float the original c template function can accept any numerical c type but this wrapper only instantiates the template with double cython convert np float to double if there s demand i can add support for other type emd with flow the flow matrix doe not contain the flow to from the extra mass bin emd sample using the default bin auto result in an extra call to np histogram to determine the bin length since the numpy bin selector are not exposed in the public api for performance you may want to set the bin yourself to help develop pyemd fork the project on github and install the requirement with pip install r requirement txt the makefile defines some task to help with development test run the test suitebuild generate and compile the cython extensionclean remove the compiled cython extensiondefault run buildtests for different python environment can be run with tox all credit for the actual algorithm and implementation go to ofir pele and michael werman see the relevant paper thanks to the cython developer for making this kind of wrapper relatively easy to write ofir pele and michael werman a linear time histogram metric for improved sift matching computer vision eccv marseille france pp ofir pele and michael werman fast and robust earth mover s distance proc ieee th int conf on computer vision kyoto japan pp

including image recognition detection segmentation generation differentiable rendering geometric learning reinforcement learning etc the front end language is python module design and dynamic graph execution is used in the front end which is the most popular design for deeplearning framework interface the back end is implemented by high performance language such a cuda c related link the following example show how to model a two layer neural network step by step and train from scratch in a few line of python code we provide some jupyter notebook to help you quick start with jittor jittor environment requirement jittor offer three way to install pip docker or manual please first install additional dependency with homebrew then you can install jittor through pip and run the example currently jittor only support cpu in macos in window jittor will automatically detect and install cuda please make sure your nvidia driver support cuda or above or you can manually let jittor for example if you want to know all the operation which jittor support try help jt ops all the operation you found in jt ops xxx can be used via alias jt xxx if you want to know more about jittor
