description: this project calculates approximate sdfs for triangle mesh it work for non watertight mesh mesh with hole self intersecting mesh mesh with non manifold geometry and mesh with inconsistently oriented face if you re using window or mac you need to work around a bug in pyrender check the faq below the mesh to voxels function creates an n n n array of sdf value in this example a mesh is reconstructed using marching cube and then rendered this example creates point where most of the point are close to the surface and some are sampled uniformly this is the method that is proposed and used in the deepsdf paper in this example the resulting point are rendered in red where the sdf is positive and in blue where it is negative the general pipeline for calculating sdf in this project is a follows this repository contains an implementation of the procedure proposed in the deepsdf paper a well a some alternative q i m getting this error module pyglet gl ha no attribute xlib this is due to a bug in pyrender possible workarounds q i want to run this on a computer without a screen ie via ssh add this to your script before importing mesh to sdf q there are cone shaped artifact in the sdf volume when using sign method normal this is a known issue to mitigate this the sign are determined by checking a number of surface point and using a majority vote this problem can t be avoided entirely and increasing the number of point normal sample count even further doesn t seem to help in some case this problem appears when the mesh contains tiny triangle that face in a different direction than their surrounding area smoothing the mesh doesn t seem to help the sign method depth approach doesn t have this problem but it doesn t work with mesh that have hole q there are ray shaped artifact in the sdf volume when using sign method depth this happens when the mesh ha hole and a camera can see inside the mesh use sign method normal instead q this doesn t work this repository contains two approximate method and in some case they don t provide usable result when one of the method fails try the other one this can be automated by using the built in way to check if the result is plausible for the voxelizing method use check result true this check if the difference in sdf is smaller than the difference in distance between any two point in sample sdf near surface you can add a volume check min size if these check fail a badmeshexception is thrown this method can process about of the mesh in the shapenet dataset calculate signed distance value for an array of given query pointsparametersreturnscalculate an n n n voxel volume of signed distance value for a given mesh the mesh is first transformed to fit inside a cube ranging from to parametersreturnsreturns additionally if return gradient is true sample some point uniformly and some point near the shape surface and calculate sdfs for these point this follows the procedure proposed in the deepsdf paper the mesh is first transformed to fit inside the unit sphere parametersreturnsreturns additionally if return gradient is true return an intermediate data structure containing a surface point cloud scan and a kd tree of the point cloud this can be used if sdfs will be calculated multiple time for the same mesh or for debugging parametersreturnssurface point method the method to generate a surface point cloud either scan or sample the scanning method creates virtual scan while the sampling method us the triangle to sample surface point the sampling method only work with watertight mesh with correct face normal but avoids some of the artifact that the scanning method creates sign method the method to determine the sign of the sdf value either normal or depth the normal method us normal of the point cloud it work better for mesh with hole but sometimes result in bubble artifact the depth method avoids the bubble artifact but is le accurate bounding radius the radius of a sphere that contains all mesh vertex if none this value is calculated using the mesh scan count number of scan when using the scanning methodscan resolution resolution for the scan in pixel sample point count number of point to sample when using surface point method sample normal sample count number of nearby surface point to check when using sign method normal the sign of the resulting sdf is determined by majority vote

description: probabilistic programming with numpy powered by jax for autograd and jit compilation to gpu tpu cpu doc and example forumnumpyro is a lightweight probabilistic programming library that provides a numpy backend for pyro we rely on jax for automatic differentiation and jit compilation to gpu cpu numpyro is under active development so beware of brittleness bug and change to the api a the design evolves numpyro is designed to be lightweight and focus on providing a flexible substrate that user can build on let u explore numpyro using a simple example we will use the eight school example from gelman et al bayesian data analysis sec which study the effect of coaching on sat performance in eight school the data is given by where y are the treatment effect and sigma the standard error we build a hierarchical model for the study where we assume that the group level parameter theta for each school are sampled from a normal distribution with unknown mean mu and standard deviation tau while the observed data are in turn generated from a normal distribution with mean and standard deviation given by theta true effect and sigma respectively this allows u to estimate the population level parameter mu and tau by pooling from all the observation while still allowing for individual variation amongst the school using the group level theta parameter let u infer the value of the unknown parameter in our model by running mcmc using the no u turn sampler nut note the usage of the extra field argument in mcmc run by default we only collect sample from the target posterior distribution when we run inference using mcmc however collecting additional field like potential energy or the acceptance probability of a sample can be easily achieved by using the extra field argument for a list of possible field that can be collected see the hmcstate object in this example we will additionally collect the potential energy for each sample we can print the summary of the mcmc run and examine if we observed any divergence during inference additionally since we collected the potential energy for each of the sample we can easily compute the expected log joint density the value above for the split gelman rubin diagnostic r hat indicates that the chain ha not fully converged the low value for the effective sample size n eff particularly for tau and the number of divergent transition look problematic fortunately this is a common pathology that can be rectified by using a non centered paramaterization for tau in our model this is straightforward to do in numpyro by using a transformeddistribution instance together with a reparameterization effect handler let u rewrite the same model but instead of sampling theta from a normal mu tau we will instead sample it from a base normal distribution that is transformed using an affinetransform note that by doing so numpyro run hmc by generating sample theta base for the base normal distribution instead we see that the resulting chain doe not suffer from the same pathology the gelman rubin diagnostic is for all the parameter and the effective sample size look quite good note that for the class of distribution with loc scale parameter such a normal cauchy studentt we also provide a locscalereparam reparameterizer to achieve the same purpose the corresponding code will benow let u assume that we have a new school for which we have not observed any test score but we would like to generate prediction numpyro provides a predictive class for such a purpose note that in the absence of any observed data we simply use the population level parameter to generate prediction the predictive utility condition the unobserved mu and tau site to value drawn from the posterior distribution from our last mcmc run and run the model forward to generate prediction for some more example on specifying model and doing inference in numpyro pyro user will note that the api for model specification and inference is largely the same a pyro including the distribution api by design however there are some important core difference reflected in the internals that user should be aware of e g in numpyro there is no global parameter store or random state to make it possible for u to leverage jax s jit compilation also user may need to write their model in a more functional style that work better with jax refer to faq for a list of difference we provide an overview of most of the inference algorithm supported by numpyro and offer some guideline about which inference algorithm may be appropriate for different class of model like hmc nut all remaining mcmc algorithm support enumeration over discrete latent variable if possible see restriction enumerated site need to be marked with infer enumerate parallel like in the annotation example see the doc for more detail limited window support note that numpyro is untested on window and might require building jaxlib from source see this jax issue for more detail alternatively you can install window subsystem for linux and use numpyro on it a on a linux system see also cuda on window subsystem for linux and this forum post if you want to use gpus on window to install numpyro with the latest cpu version of jax you can use pip in case of compatibility issue arise during execution of the above command you can instead force the installation of a known compatible cpu version of jax withto use numpyro on the gpu you need to install cuda first and then use the following pip command if you need further guidance please have a look at the jax gpu installation instruction to run numpyro on cloud tpus you can look at some jax on cloud tpu example for cloud tpu vm you need to setup the tpu backend a detailed in the cloud tpu vm jax quickstart guide after you have verified that the tpu backend is properly set up you can install numpyro using the pip install numpyro command default platform jax will use gpu by default if cuda supported jaxlib package is installed you can use set platform utility numpyro set platform cpu to switch to cpu at the beginning of your program you can also install numpyro from source you can also install numpyro with conda unlike in pyro numpyro sample x dist normal doe not work why you are most likely using a numpyro sample statement outside an inference context jax doe not have a global random state and a such distribution sampler need an explicit random number generator key prngkey to generate sample from numpyro s inference algorithm use the seed handler to thread in a random number generator key behind the scene your option are call the distribution directly and provide a prngkey e g dist normal sample prngkey provide the rng key argument to numpyro sample e g numpyro sample x dist normal rng key prngkey wrap the code in a seed handler used either a a context manager or a a function that wrap over the original callable e g or a a higher order function can i use the same pyro model for doing inference in numpyro a you may have noticed from the example numpyro support all pyro primitive like sample param plate and module and effect handler additionally we have ensured that the distribution api is based on torch distribution and the inference class like svi and mcmc have the same interface this along with the similarity in the api for numpy and pytorch operation ensures that model containing pyro primitive statement can be used with either backend with some minor change example of some difference along with the change needed are noted below for most small model change required to run inference in numpyro should be minor additionally we are working on pyro api which allows you to write the same code and dispatch it to multiple backends including numpyro this will necessarily be more restrictive but ha the advantage of being backend agnostic see the documentation for an example and let u know your feedback how can i contribute to the project thanks for your interest in the project you can take a look at beginner friendly issue that are marked with the good first issue tag on github also please feel to reach out to u on the forum in the near term we plan to work on the following please open new issue for feature request and enhancement the motivating idea behind numpyro and a description of iterative nut can be found in this paper that appeared in neurips program transformation for machine learning workshop if you use numpyro please consider citing a well a
